<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's One-Child Policy Produces Friendlier, More Confident Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Children born during the
two-decade-old "One Couple, One Child" policy are eager to make
friends, more self-confident, more willing to help others and
improve themselves, and have a wider range of interests, latest
survey results said today.
</P>
<P>
The results of a survey conducted by the China Youth Research
Center and the China Youth Development Foundation of more than
3,000 children of one-child families in 12 cities were released
today.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that these so-called "young emperors" do have
some weak-points. Only 12.8 percent have great expectations or
ambition, even though most of the parents want them to amount to
something. This indicates that the child spoiled by parents
doesn't feel the motive of working for a lofty goal quite as
easily.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that 88.4 percent of the children are
narrow-minded, bad-tempered, and are quick to attack anyone who
teases or insults them.
</P>
<P>
Children from one-child families also lack creativity, a sense
of independence, and a willingness to work hard or be thrifty.
</P>
<P>
Only a small part of the children questioned showed a strong
desire for study. This indicates that the present educational
system, with its barrage of tests and exam, has made competition
among school-children too intense and, as a result, has caused
them to lose interest.
</P>
<P>
The researchers said that family education, schooling and
friends are the three most important factors in children's morals,
and they suggest that the present educational system be changed,
with greater importance being placed on providing healthier
natures in children from one-child families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
