<HEADLINE> Iran Scores World Record in World Cup Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The soccer's world governing body
said on Tuesday that Iran has set a world record as it blanked the
Maldives 17-0 in an Asian zone qualifier on Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, its striker Karim Bakeri's seven-goal spree could not
yet be recognised as a world record since details of early World
Cup qualifiers were still incomplete.
</P>
<P>
The incredible mark of 17-0 set in Damascus beat the previous
best of 13-0, set by New Zealand against Fiji in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Bakeri scored his first three in a five-minute spell in the
first half, followed by another six-minute hat-trick between the
62nd and 68th minutes before completing his tally five minutes
from time.
</P>
<P>
Currently no player had ever scored seven goals in a World Cup
match.
</P>
<P>
Iran's win marked the 14th time in World Cup history where one
team has scored at least 10 goals. Apart from Hungary's 10-1 win
over El Salvador in the 1982 finals in Spain, all were in the
qualifiers including four for next year's World Cup finals in
France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
