<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Calls for Protecting Arctic Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF)
today urged environment ministers from Arctic nations to take action
to protect Arctic wildlife and indigenous peoples from a rising tide
of pollution.
</P>
<P>
A study by the Arctic Monitoring and Assessment Program (AMAP)
shows widespread persistent organic pollutants, heavy metals and
radionuclides in the Arctic, making indigenous peoples and wildlife in
the region among the most highly exposed populations, a WWF press
release said.
</P>
<P>
Environment ministers from Denmark, Finland, Greenland,
Iceland, Norway, Russia, Sweden and the United States are due to
meet next week in Alta, Norway to discuss the report released
Monday after a six-year study co-sponsored by the eight Arctic
countries.
</P>
<P>
The WWF calls on the ministers to quickly conclude negotiations
on three new protocols dealing with local and transboundary
regulation of persistent organic pollutants, heavy metals and
nitrogen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
