<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat to Visit Egypt Early Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat is due to arrive here tomorrow morning for talks
with President Hosni Mubarak on the deadlocked Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al-Kodrah, breaking the
news to the Egyptian MENA news agency, said that the meeting, the
second in two weeks in continued consultations, aims at "serving
the Palestinian cause."
</P>
<P>
Kodrah hailed Egypt for its support to the Palestinian people's
legitimate right and demands, and extolled the efforts exerted by
Mubarak to break the current impasse in the peace march.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said the Palestinians support all Egyptian
drives to halt the Israeli settlement activities in the occupied
territories, including Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's trip came a week after Mubarak met with Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in the Red Sea resort of Sharm
el-Sheikh in a bid to broke ice in the peace process which stalled
after Israel began building a new Jewish quarters in Arab East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who reportedly is floating an initiative to narrow the
difference between the Israelis and Palestinians, had hoped to
bring together Arafat and Netanyahu at a tripartite summit.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat's spokesman said such a meeting would be meaningless
when Israel continues its settlement construction in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
As part of intensified Egyptian mediation efforts, Mubarak's
political advisor Osama al-Baz left here this morning for a
four-day visit to the U.S., a co-sponsor of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He will brief the U.S. administration on his several shuttle
trips to the PA and Israel in the past few days in a bid to bring
the two sides back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office said the Egyptian efforts made "some
progress," but Palestinian sources said that Baz failed to get
Israeli response to the Palestinian demand.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made their return to the negotiating
table conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary policy.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's five-point plan aimed at persuading the two sides to
the table includes a temporary halt of settlement activities in
Jerusalem and the West Bank and the resumption of
Palestinian-Israeli security coordination.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has refused to stop the Har Homa construction and
instead proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the Jewish
housing project. He also proposed measures to ease the limitations
against the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
