<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Meddling in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi
said here today Nigeria is trying to restore order in Sierra
Leone whose government was ousted in a military coup last month.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi said that his country had sent its forces to help Sierra
Leone in pursuit of the common goal of trying to bring peace and
stability to the west African region.
</P>
<P>
''This is not interference,'' he said, adding, ''We, as ECOWAS
(the Economic Community of West African States), have always been
interested in explosive situations that take place in our region
which we see as endangering civilians lives and disturb peace.''
</P>
<P>
He said, ''Together with the international community we must
not allow such a situation to continue.''
</P>
<P>
''Nigeria is going to ensure that peace, stability and a
legitimate government are restored in Sierra Leone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah was ousted from
power by rebels led by Major Johnny Koromah on Africa Day.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and the Organisation of African Unity (OAU)
have condemned the coup and demanded that rebel leaders should
restore the ousted government.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi is representing Nigerian Head of State Sani AbachA to
attend the 33rd summit conference of the Organization of African
Unity in Harare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
