<HEADLINE> Japanese Government Launches Spending Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government today agreed
on a program of spending cuts to keep expenditure in the fiscal
1998 national budget below this year's level as the first step
toward repairing the country's battered finances.
</P>
<P>
The government's general or policy-related expenditures in
fiscal 1998, which begins next April, will be trimmed by some 200
billion yen (1.7 billion U.S. dollars), or 0.5 percent, to 43.6
trillion yen (379 billion dollars) from the budgeted spending of
43.8 trillion yen (380.8 billion dollars) for fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
Increases in social security spending will be kept to some 300
billion yen (2.6 billion dollars) and spending on public works
will be cut by at least 7 percent or 630 billion yen (5.5 billion
dollars) over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to cut Japan's annual defense
budget by 3 percent on a year-on-year basis between fiscal 1998
and 2000, excluding spending needed for the transfer and return of
the U.S. military bases in Okinawa Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Assistance for developing countries will be slashed by 10
percent, or 110 billion yen (0.96 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The spending cuts are aimed at reducing the government's
budget deficit which, at seven percent in the year to March 1997,
is the worst in the industrialized world. The government aims to
reduce the ratio to three percent by 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
