<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President for African Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
said here today that African countries has no alternative but to
integrate their small markets into a large single market in front of
the challenge of world-wide economic development.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the remarks while addressing the inaugural summit of
the African Economic Community at the Organization of African Unity
meeting. He is current Chairman of the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said that Africa should organize its home market first if it
is to take advantage of the opening of trade opportunities offered
under the current Uruguay Round agreements and the World Trade
Organization rules.
</P>
<P>
"If we remain divided, small and relatively weak," Chiluba said,
"then we shall open ourselves to manipulation and marginalization as
manifested in adverse terms of trade, restricted trade and commodity
quarters, segregative standards, transfer pricing and many other such
prohibitive practices we continue to experience in global
transactions."
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "We need to approach the world
economy from the strong position of unity with a strong bargaining
position" to "confront the adversities of the open advanced global
economy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
