<HEADLINE> Software Becoming America's No.3 Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The computer software business has
risen rapidly to become America's third-largest manufacturing
industry, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by Nathan Associates, an economic
consulting firm, found that the American software industry
generated revenues of 102.8 billion U.S. dollars last year. Since
1990, the software industry has grown at a rate of 12.5 percent
annually, nearly 2.5 times faster than the economy as a whole.
</P>
<P>
On the value-added basis, software ranked third after
automobiles and electronics. In a 1995 study, software ranked
fifth, behind the aircraft and pharmaceutical industry as well as
autos and electronics.
</P>
<P>
The study, which provides the most detailed portrait to date of
the jobs and wealth generated by the fast-growing software
industry, is intended to emphasize the rising importance of the
software industry, the New York Times said in a report today.
</P>
<P>
The industry-sponsored research will be presented to Washington
Wednesday by a group of computer executives led by Bill Gates of
Microsoft and Andrew Grove of Intel, two giants in U.S. computer
software business.
</P>
<P>
"We see the study as a framework for saying to leaders in
Washington that software is major engine of the modern economy,"
Robert Holleyman, president of the Business Software Alliance, was
quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
