<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian PM Appoints Four Women MPs as Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral today appointed four women MPs as cabinet ministers in a
move to give adequate representation to women in his government.
</P>
<P>
This is the first expansion of the Gujral cabinet since it was
installed on April 21. With the inclusion of the four women
members, the present Council of Ministers has raised its strength
to 44.
</P>
<P>
All the four new comers will be ministers of state in the
cabinet. President S.D. Sharma administered the oath of office to
the new ministers at a simple ceremony at the Rashtrapati Bhawan
(president building).
</P>
<P>
The forty-three-year-old Jayanthi Natarajan, an articulate
lawyer-turned-politician, hails from a traditionally Congress
party family and is the grand daughter of former Tamil Nadu chief
minister M. Bakthavatsalam.
</P>
<P>
Kamla Sinha is a veteran trade union leader from Bihar state
while Ratnamala Savanoor is a well-known social worker.
</P>
<P>
A fourth woman politician inducted into the central Government
today is Renuka Chaudhury, who is regarded as an extremely vocal
and aggressive member of the upper house of parliament. She has
been a member of parliament for over a decade.
</P>
<P>
The inclusion of more women members into the cabinet is in
keeping with Gujral's commitment to giving adequate representation
to women in his government.
</P>
<P>
The move is also seen as an attempt to placate women MPs who
have been resentful of the concerted bid to block passage of a
women bill to reserve one-third of seats in the parliament and
state assemblies for women. The United Front government tabled the
women bill before parliament last year, but it has so far failed
to be passed due to strong opposition from various parties and men
MPs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
