<HEADLINE> Arafat Accuses Israel of Breaching Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Leader Yasser Arafat
said today that Israel was planning to offer only 40 percent of
the West Bank to Palestinians as part of a final peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who was here attending the Organization of African
Unity's 33rd summit to lobby support from African leaders against
Israel, told reporters that "This is not the first time the
Israelis are breaching the agreement signed at the white house
(in Washington)".
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has denied the
alleged plan.
</P>
<P>
The alleged plan would allow Israel to annex or maintain
control over at least 60 percent of the West Bank captured by
Israel along with the Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem in the 1967
Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians demand full control over all the occupied
territories for the creation of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to the peace process, but the other side is
not," Arafat said. "Netanyahu has shown that he is against past
agreements."
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the construction of Jewish settlements in Arab
east Jerusalem, which began two months ago, was another
indication that Netanyahu was not committed to peace.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Council of Ministers recommended at the end of its
meeting last week in Harare that the African summit call on
Israel to stop the construction of the settlements.
</P>
<P>
"What was agreed upon at the ministerial level is very strong
and we, at the same time, are grateful for the continuous support
we get from the summit to our cause," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
On reports that some of Palestinian officials had sold land to
Jews, Arafat said an investigation would be launched and culprits
be brought to court.
</P>
<P>
"There is a law and we are following that law agaisnt those
who sold the land," Arafat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
