<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jospin to Set Up "Clean" Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- France's new Socialist Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin has indicated that he will set up a "clean"
government whose members are not involved or suspected of being
involved in any corruption case.
</P>
<P>
Socialist officials also said that the new left government of
France will be pluralistic, including members from the Communist
Party, the radical Socialists, the Greens and other leftwing party
members.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet will comprise 15 ministers and several state
secretaries, and women ministers are expected to play a big role
in it, said Socialist officials.
</P>
<P>
Jospin has already named Olivier Schrameck as the director of
his cabinet, and Jean-Pierre Jouyet assistant director of the
cabinet, while the list of ministers is expected to be published
Wednesday or Thursday, before Jospin leaves for Malmoe, Sweden, to
attend a Socialist summit of Europe.
</P>
<P>
No government officials will be allowed to hold a second post
or to be on a second payroll, and Jospin himself will resign from
the post as Socialist Party chief in November, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
Jospin today formally took over the prime minister's office
from Alain Juppe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
