<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Earnings Fall Short of Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Export earnings by Bangladesh's four
major foreign exchange earning sectors -- garments, leather,
frozen foods, and jute goods -- fell short of their planned target
by about 397 million U.S. dollars during the first 10 months of
the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Export Promotion Bureau (EPB), earnings by
ready-made garments fell short of its target by 160 million
dollars, frozen foods by 95 million dollars, jute goods by 66
million dollars and leather by 75 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The four sectors normally account for 75 percent of the
country's total annual export earnings.
</P>
<P>
Exports of petroleum products, tea, handicrafts and electronic
goods also failed to reach their targets during the July-April
period of the 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
However, some agricultural goods, chemical and engineering
products, knitwear and other "minor sectors" performed "better
than expected" and helped minimize the shortfall, said the EPB.
</P>
<P>
The target for the first 10 months of fiscal 1996-97 was 3.83
billion dollars and the earnings stood at 3.78 billion dollars,
leaving a shortfall of about 50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government has set the target of export earnings for fiscal
1996-97 as 4.599 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AEC's Inaugural Session Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- African leaders today held the
first inaugural session of the African Economic Community (AEC)
which is set to become a force in ridding the continent of
poverty and deprivation.
</P>
<P>
The session was convened on the sideline of the 33rd summit of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU). The summit entrusted
OAU's Council of Ministers to be the highest organ surpervising
the AEC.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who assumed the
chaimanship of the 53-member OAU on monday, said the
establishment of the highest organ of the AEC constituted a
standard by which Africa's future economic policies would be
judged by Africans and outsiders.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the event, witnessed by 28 heads of state and
government and three prime ministers, crowned efforts stretching
several decades made by the OAU, resulting in several resolutions
and declarations which laid a firm political foundation for the
establishment of AEC.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe noted that the pillars of the AEC were the African
regional integration bodies specified in the Abuja Treaty adopted
in 1991, which came into force in 1994.
</P>
<P>
What African countries now need to do, said Mugabe, was to
integrate their markets and transform their economies currently
characterised by low levels of industrialization, high dependence
on international trade, extremely low levels of intra-African
trade and small markets.
</P>
<P>
He said the AEC should make it possible for African countries
to produce competitive products that would enjoy preferential
treatment in African markets.
</P>
<P>
African countries, he said, faced a hostile external economic
environment induced by forces outside its control.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, African countries were exporters of raw
materials and minerals whose prices they did not control.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, the value of exports had been declining and
yet the cost of importing manufactured products had been on the
increase, Mugabe added.
</P>
<P>
He criticised the world trade organization and international
financial institutions for taking hostile policies towards Africa
and the entire developing world.
</P>
<P>
"It would appear that there is a coordinated political agenda
by the north, which controls these institutions, aimed at
suppressing the development of developing countries," said
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
He called on African countries to strengthen solidarity with
other affected developing countries in creating a just and
equitable international economic order.
</P>
<P>
"Together we must resist the recololization of our countries
under a facade of programs to safeguard the global environment or
globalization," Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
He said the inaugural session of the AEC had sent a strong
signal that it was now empowering itself to defeat the
indignities of poverty, hunger and disease through joint actions
in social, economic and political fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
