<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Futures Exchange Trades Record May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The London International Financial
Futures and Options Exchange (LIFFE) traded a record of 16,597,319
contracts in May, 33 percent up on May 1996.
</P>
<P>
Average daily volume amounted to 829,866 futures and options
contracts, representing a daily nominal turnover of 163 billion
pounds (266 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Statistics released today show that since the beginning of this
year, the LIFFE's cumulative volume has totaled 83,946,904 futures
and options contracts, a rise of 19 percent over the same period
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The historic link between the LIFFE and the Chicago Board of
Trade (CBOT), whereby the LIFFE trades the CBOT's 30 Year Treasury
(T-Bond) futures and options contracts and the CBOT trades the
LIFFE's 10 Year German Government Bond futures and options
contracts, was inaugurated on May 9.
</P>
<P>
To date, a total of 26,873 T-Bond futures and options contracts
have been traded at the LIFFE and a total of 115,479 futures and
options contracts have been traded at the CBOT.
</P>
<P>
Jack Wigglesworth, chairman of the LIFFE, said, "We are
extremely pleased with the success of the link so far. When the
Bundesbank made its announcement on May 28, the CBOT traded a
record number of LIFFE Bond contracts on its floor. The LIFFE's
alliance with the CBOT is providing opportunities for both
exchanges, now and in the future, and we look forward to watching
the progress of both contracts."
</P>
<P>
Factors such as the British elections, continuing speculation
over Italian entry to Economic and Monetary Union and a
speculation over a possible rise in U.S. interest rates have
contributed to record volume for the month of May, according to
the chairman.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The LIFFE's position as the largest futures and
options exchange outside Chicago is thus maintained, providing an
efficient, well-regulated environment for the management of
international interest rate and Britain's stock market risk."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
