<HEADLINE> Mobutu's Assets Worth 3.5 Mln Dlrs Found in Switzerland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss Banking Commission
announced today that former Zairian leader Mobutu Sese Seko's
assets found in six Swiss banks are only less than 5 million Swiss
francs (about 3.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The assets including foreign shares, bonds, securities and a
safe deposit box have been frozen. The sum of 4,786,570 Swiss
francs (about 3.5 million U.S. dollars) is far below the figure of
7.7 billion U.S. dollars which new Zairian authorities led by
Laurent Kabila claimed that Mobutu and his family members had
transferred to Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
On May 17, the Swiss Federal Council (federal government)
ordered to freeze all of Mobutu's assets in Switzerland. The Swiss
government announced that the decision to freeze the assets of
Mobutu and his family members entered into force immediately as
Mobutu no long exercised the function of a Zairian president.
</P>
<P>
Also on that day, the Swiss government ordered all
organizations administering Mobutu's assets in Switzerland to
report at once to the federal finance department.
</P>
<P>
On May 16, the Swiss federal government decided to freeze
Mobutu's 5.5-million-dollar villa in Savigny, Vaud, about 60
kilometers northeast of Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
