<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States today began a
new phase of evacuation of Americans and other foreigners from
troubled Sierra Leone following reports of violence resulting from
a military coup.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Marines using helicopters evacuated another 1,217
foreigners, including about 20 Americans, from the capital of
Freetown, the Defense Department said. That brought to nearly
2,500 the total number of persons, including some 430 Americans,
removed since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There have been no casualties. It has been a well-run
operation. They are all out," Defense Secretary William Cohen told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
