<HEADLINE> African Leaders Adopt UNIDO Industrial Plan for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The African leaders attending the 33rd
summit of the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) today adopted a
United Nations Industrial Development Organisation (UNIDO) sponsored
industrial plan for Africa.
</P>
<P>
The plan, dubbed the Alliance for Africa's Industrialisation
(AAI), seeks to promote integrated industrialisation in Africa
through sharing of information, resources and expertise.
</P>
<P>
The modalities of how to achieve that would soon be worked out by
a patron group of five heads of state led by Cote d'Ivoire's Konan
Bedie.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference soon after the adoption of the plan,
Ivorian Industry Minister Theophile Ahoua N'doli said, ''The goals of
the AAI include institutional capacity building, linking industry and
agriculture to enhance productivity and agro-industry sector
competitiveness, promoting growth of small and medium scale
industries and promoting private investment and technology
transfor.''
</P>
<P>
N'doli added the heads of state and government recognised that
without sustainable industrial development, african economies would be
condemned to persistent economic crises.
</P>
<P>
the leaders requested that UNIDO, in cooperation with the AEC and
the OAU secretariat, to organise a donor conference that would start
off the program by next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
