<HEADLINE> Four Militants Killed in Southern Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Security forces gunned down four
Muslim militants in southern Egypt in a fierce clash Monday night,
Interior Minister Hassan el-Alfi said today.
</P>
<P>
The fire exchange occurred in Samalut, Minya, 200 kilometers
southwest of Cairo, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The killed, all in their twenties, were identified as members
of the Al Gamaa Al Islamiya, or the Islamic Group that has been
blamed for a spate of recent assassinations in the south.
</P>
<P>
The four men were involved in the killing of nine Coptic
Christians during an attack on a nearby church on February 13,
el-Alfi said.
</P>
<P>
Two of the four rifles found Monday night at the scene belonged
to two police recruits who were killed in a terrorist attack in
Minya in 1995, the Egyptian MENA news agency quoted an Interior
official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government has tightened the noose around the Islamic
militants who have been fighting to set up an Islamic rule since
1992.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,050 people have been killed in the violence and
most of them were police and militants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
