<HEADLINE> Botswana Plans Industrial Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Botswanan government is
mapping out a framework for the privatization of some government
enterprises in a bid to speed up development of national economy,
said reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Although policy is still being formulated, the government has
already indicated that the partial privatization is likely to
affect state-owned departments, such as Botswana
Telecommunications Corporation, Air Botswana and the Botswana
Livestock Development Corporation, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Botswana Confederation of Commerce, Industry and Manpower
has urged the governemnt to privatize enterprises such as
Botswana Railways, Botswana Meat Commission, the Central Tender
Board and Botswana Housing Corportation.
</P>
<P>
The confederation has been engaged in campaign for
privatization of state-owned enterprises, hoping it will enable
them to compete in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We have to learn to do business with little protection and to
compete with other business. This is crucial since the world is
moving towards open markets," Botswanan policy co-ordinator
Ditshaba Molobe said.
</P>
<P>
However, Botswana's move to privatization has also been met
with caution in other quarters amid warnings that the transfer of
government assets should be handled delicately.
</P>
<P>
"Traditionally, govenrments have been privatizing sectors
which are seen to be inefficient, but that does not guarantee
success," said Sennye Obuseng, Economics Lecturer of
Botswana University.
</P>
<P>
Obuseng pointed out the big problem in Botswana is that few
people with capital or sufficient
expertise can run enterprises simlilar to the one run by the
government.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not very optimistic that the government will get buyers
who can provide what the government cannot provide now," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some parties in Botswana also criticize that
privatization will simply mean giving away national assets to
foreign companies because locals cannot affort to buy them.

