<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Embargo Worsens Iraqis' Health Status: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. air embargo and delayed
delivery of medicine and medical supplies have seriously worsened
the health status of the Iraqi people, a local English-language
newspaper reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Baghdad Observer quoted a recent survey conducted by the
Iraqi Health Ministry as saying that the air embargo, which was
imposed on Iraq by the U.N. Security Council after the country
invaded Kuwait in August, 1990, has caused the death of 1,918
Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
The survey blamed this situation on the air embargo as well
as the lack of medicine and medical facilities, such as
ambulances in particular, which have made it almost impossible
to transfer swiftly Iraqi patients from one place to another or
to facilitate their necessary treatment abroad.
</P>
<P>
The problem in Iraq is not that doctors are unable to treat
the patients, rather they do not have medicines and other
essential medical supplies, said the paper, stressing that many
of the patients would have been treated locally if necessary
medical supplies had been available.
</P>
<P>
However, up till now only 60 tonnes of medicines have arrived
in Iraq, a country with a total population of 20 million.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Health Minister Omed Medhat Mubarak said recently at a
news conference that the sufferings of Iraqis are even greater
now than seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
Before the U.N. sanctions were imposed in 1990, the mortality
rate for Iraqi children under age five averaged 540 a month, but
"it has now reached 5,600 and is still growing," according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was allowed to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil
to buy food, medicine and other necessities in accordance with
an "oil-for-food" deal with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has asked the U.N. for permission to fly Iraqi patients
abroad for medical treatment, but has received no answer yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
