<HEADLINE> Chinese Language Teaching Due to Begin in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- China will help Kenya to start
Chinese-language teaching and studying, according to an
accord on bilateral educational cooperation signed by
the two governments here today.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Kenyan Education Minister J. Kamotho
and Wei Yu, the visiting Vice-Minister of China's State Education
Commission, after their talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, China will dispatch a teacher to the Egerton
University in southwestern Kenya, to teach Chinese and donate
necessary textbooks.
</P>
<P>
China will also provide laboratory equipment, reagents and
books to help the Egerton University advance horticultural
teaching and research.
</P>
<P>
Two Chinese professors have been at the university since 1995
to train teachers and students there on the development of
applied technology of horticulture in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
During the talks with Wei, the Kenyan education minister said
the two countries have a long-standing cooperation especially in
the education and cultural sectors and expressed his government's
appreciation of Chinese support to Kenya's development.
</P>
<P>
Wei, in fluent English, reaffirmed China's continuous support
to the eastern African country.
</P>
<P>
Wei, leading a five-member educational delegation, arrived
here on Saturday and will leave for Zimbabwe tomorrow. 
</P>
