<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Livestock Holders Association to Be Formed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 3 (Xinhua) --Tanzanian Minister for Agriculture and
Co-operatives Paul Kimiti, today urged livestock holders to set
up a mechanism that will facilitate the development of the livestock
sector in the country.
</P>
<P>
Opening a meeting on the promotion of the Stakeholders Association
formation, Kimiti said the contribution of the livestock sector, which
makes some 18 percent of the country's Gross Domestic Product (GDP),
was still very low compared to the large livestock and vast rangeland
resources.
</P>
<P>
He said, according to 1994/95 national sample census of
agriculture, Tanzania had 15.6 million cattle, 10.6 million goats, 3.5
million sheep and some 27 million chickens.
</P>
<P>
The government had been facing problems in the
choice of policies to suit both suppliers and consumers so as to meet
the consumer demand for livestock products, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kimiti said such a mechanism, would therefore, facilitate a
dialogue between the government and the private sector hence adoption
of policies that would suit the interests of both the supplier and the
consumer.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was also intending to facilitate the
formation of other livestock stakeholders like dairy farmers, meat
processors, livestock input suppliers, dairy processors and animal
feeds manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, attended by livestock holders,
officials from the ministry and academiciians, a 10-man task force was
formed that would recommend on the structure of the proposed livestock
holders association within two months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
