<HEADLINE> WFP Airlifts Refugees from Former Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program (WFP)
has airlifted some 45,000 refugees from former Zaire back to
their homes in Rwanda since the end of April, the WFP Regional
Information Office said here today.
</P>
<P>
The "food in-people out" initiative, one of WFP's most complex
operations, also gets supports from the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees, said the office.
</P>
<P>
WFP has since December airlifted 10,000 tons of relief food
into Kisangani, the third largest city in former Zaire, now
the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The city was the base of operations for all humanitarian
agencies trying to reach refugees in the war-torn central
African country.
</P>
<P>
The six-month operation estimatedly costs WFP 14 million U.S.
Dollars with more than 1,300 hours of flight time involved.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen WFP aircraft including a Boeing 707 were deployed
from nine bases in six countries to join the operation.
</P>
<P>
WFP, the main logistical arm of the U.N., airlifts some 60,000
travelers, mostly relief workers, each year to 14 countries,
said the office. enditem


