<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Action in Freetown Not to Create Loopholes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The current military action of the
west African peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG in Sierra Leone
would not create loopholes in Liberia, a Nigerian defense
spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen in Lagos, the spokesman, Colonel Godwin Ugbo
said the drafting of more troops from Liberia to Sierra Leone
would not jeopardize security in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
What is happening in Liberia now is only a search for hidden
arms in the 13 counties of the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The borders have been sealed off to prevent entry of weapons
into Liberia," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that there are now enough troops in
Liberia and additional troops would not be needed from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander, Major-General Victor Malu said
recently that there are now nearly 11,000 ECOMOG soldiers in
Liberia, while the number of troops in Freetown is now about
3,600. 
