<HEADLINE> Annan Wants Peaceful Solution to Sierra Leone's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary General Kofi Annan
today called for a peaceful solution to the crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Annan told a press conference that African countries and the
international community should do whatever they could to get the coup
leaders in Sierra Leone step down and restore the legitimate and
elected government.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who was here attending the 33rd summit of african
countries, expressed the hope that this could be achieved without
military force.
</P>
<P>
"There is the possibility that further bloodshed can be avoided in
Sierra Leone," Annan said when asked whether outside military
intervention would be applied to reverse the coup.
</P>
<P>
Military officers in Sierra Leone toppled the civil government
in a coup in late May, drawing worldwide condemnation. Nigerian
forces bombarded Freetown, the capital of Sierra Leone in the past
few days in a bid to force the coup leaders to surrender.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he did not want the parties concerned to resort to
military means to settle the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said there would have been more bloodshed if the issue had
not been handled properly.
</P>
<P>
He called on the coup leaders to "listen to reason", saying:
"It is extremely difficult to govern a nation if your neighbors do
not accept you, the region does not accept you, the world does not
accept you and the people do not accept you."
</P>
<P>
"So I hope bloodshed can be avoided," he added.
</P>
<P>
But he indicated that if military intervention became the last
resort of option, he and African leaders would prepare to go that
way. enditem

