<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq's Oil-for-Food Plan Shows Mixed Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Implementation of the
oil-for-food plan to alleviate Iraq's humanitarian crises
presented mixed results: the value of the oil export contracts
approved nearly fulfilled the revenue objective while a large
number of import applications had been placed on hold, according
to a UN report.
</P>
<P>
The report prepared by the UN's Iraqi sanction committee said
that as at May 30, a total of 51 contracts had been submitted for
review by the UN overseers and all of them have been approved. The
oil export contracts approved, under which 121 million barrels
would be shipped overseas, were estimated at 2.16 billion dollars.
After deducting the pipeline fees, the value was similar to the
180-day revenue objective of 2 billion dollars as stipulated in
Security Council resolution 986.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food plan stipulated by the resolution was aimed at
alleviating the severe shortage of food and medicine caused by the
six-year-long economic sanctions. The UN has imposed strict
sanctions, including embargo of oil export, on Iraq after its
invasion of Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
However, import of food, medicine and other humanitarian goods
lagged far behind as the initial 180-day period for
implementation of resolution 986 would come to an end on June 7.
</P>
<P>
The UN secretariat had received 630 import applications from
Iraq as at May 30. Among the 574 of the import applications
circulated to the Iraqi sanction committee members, only 331 were
approved with a total value of 816 million dollars while 191 were
placed on hold, 14 blocked and 38 awaiting decisions of the
Committee.
</P>
<P>
On delayed action of import approval, the sanction committee,
or officially knowns as the Security Council Committee established
by resolution 661 (1990) concerning the situation between Iraq and
Kuwait, noted the process for approval of Iraq's import
applications had been one of the most complex tasks facing the
committee and the UN secretariat.
</P>
<P>
"The committee is concerned at the slow pace of contract
approval, which has been caused by a number of factors, including
the initial insufficiency of funds in the United Nations Iraq
account and deficiencies in submitted applications," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Committee members who placed holds on contracts indicated that
a major reason was that the applications were incomplete or
technically inconsistent with the approved distribution plan, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
But, the Iraqi government accused the United States of
hindering the implementation of the oil-for-food plan. "The delay
in the implementation of this humanitarian aspect of Resolution
986 is due to an insistence from the United States delegation in
the (661) committee to place a hold or block most contracts to
procure the above mentioned goods," said a recent press release of
the Iraqi mission to the UN.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, the US delegation blocks or places on hold 220
contracts out of 610 contracts circulated for approval," the Iraqi
press release said.
</P>
<P>
"This attitude is inevitably leading to the prolongation of
suffering experienced daily by the Iraqi people.... 25 percent of
Iraqi children are suffering from severe chronic malnutrition,"
the release added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
