Sudanese press reports today said Eritrean troops have been
mobilised all along the borders with the Sudan, and are armed with
modern equipment including armored vehicles and rockets.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that Eritrean troops are ready to launch an
attack to occupy the main road linking the capital of Khartoum
with the principal northern Red Sea port of Port Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The reports added the projected goal of an Eritrean offensive
is to occupy the towns of Kasala and Port Sudan and to enable the
Sudanese opposition to move into the depth of the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan has been repeatedly accusing Eritrean troops of
taking part in the fighting which has once and again erupted along
the joint borders for more than six months and has lodged a
complaint against Eritrea with the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
But the accusations were flatly denied by Eritrea, which
claimed the fighting was fought between the Sudanese government
troops and the Sudanese opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Eritrea occupied the garrisons of Atirba
and Qaroura in east Sudan last March. The Sudan then announced
its forces killed a large number of Eritrean troops during an
offensive.
</P>
<P>
The Sudan has recently closed its borders with Eritrea and is
strengthening measures against the smuggling of goods and cars,
which it alleged was carried out by Eritrea in favor of the
Sudanese opposition.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that with the intensified exchange of
accusations between the two countries, and the mobilization of
troops along the joint borders have made room for the Sudanese
opposition forces lead by John Garang to step up actions.
</P>
<P>
Border tension will also divert the Sudanese government forces
from southern Sudan to the northeast part in order to ensure the
security of Port Sudan, a fact which will actually assist the
opposition to penetrate into the depth of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
