<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Trading Structures Changing Rapidly, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The world economy is no longer based
on traditional trading structures and wealth is generated in
entirely different ways and information technology is central, a
conference was told here today.
</P>
<P>
The conference, Exploiting The Information Age, is designed to
inform UK business leaders on how the convergence of computers and
communications technologies will radically reshape the way
companies work in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales on the Internet in 1995 were valued at 312 million
pounds (499 million US dollars). By the end of the decade they are
predicted to rise to 3.7 billion pounds (5.9 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
It is forecasted by the year 2005 that 30 percent of Britain's
21 billion pounds (33.6 billion US dollars) retail sales will be
executed electronically.
</P>
<P>
As part of its ongoing drive to make the Information Age not
only accessible, but useful, to business and industry,
Hewlett-Packard (HP), a leading global provider of computing,
Internet and Intranet solutions joined forces with the
Confederation of British Industry.
</P>
<P>
Together, the two organizations are staging a series of events
to stimulate debate and help companies attain their commercial
objectives and stay ahead of competition through the efficient use
of the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
HP's chief executive, John Golding said: "We are in the midst
of a revolution - telecommunications and computing technologies
have merged and will radically alter the way we do business."
</P>
<P>
An observer from the City said, small companies with big ideas
can look to the world's finance markets for investment and venture
capital. Without today's advanced computer systems and
telecommunications networks, this would be impossible.
</P>
<P>
An information expert at the conference said:"Innovative use of
information technology is the key to gaining a competitive edge in
the emerging global market of the Information Age."
</P>
<P>
"Companies must change the way that they structure themselves
and the way that employees work together," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
