<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UK's MPC Leading Members Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Chancellor Gordon Brown
put an end to speculation on Monday by announcing the four leading
members of the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC).
</P>
<P>
The announcement was greeted with relief in the City.
Economists said the new members added credibility to the
committee, which has responsibility for fixing interest rate
policy under Chancellor's reform plans.
</P>
<P>
The appointees are Dr DeAnne Julius, chief economist at British
Airways, Sir Alan Budd, chief economic adviser at the Treasury,
and two academics, Professor Charles Goodhart and Professor Willem
Buiter.
</P>
<P>
The creation of the new committee, which meets for the first
time on Thursday and Friday, marks an important stage in the
Transfer from the Treasury to the Bank of control over interest
rates, the Chanceller announced a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The MPC appointments, which were seen as non-political and
likely to have a neutral impact on policy, were welcomed by City
economists.
</P>
<P>
Adam Cole, UK economist at HSBC James Capel, said: "The
appointments are all fairly middle of the road and there is no one
whom I would regard as especially a hawk or a dove on inflation."
</P>
<P>
Eddie Georte, the Governor of the Bank of England, said he was
"delighted" with the new members and felt certain they would make
a major contribution to the Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, City economists were divided on whether a
quarter-point rise in interest rates would be announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Cates, an economist at UBS, said he expected the first
meeting to result in rates being left alone for the time being.
</P>
</TEXT>
