<HEADLINE> PKK Kills 4 Village Guards in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Guerrillas of the illegal Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) today killed four village guards and wounded
another one in southeastern Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that a group of PKK rebels opened fired at
the village guards who were then changing shifts in Aslanbasar
village of southeastern province of Sirnak.
</P>
<P>
The guards returned fire but four of them died in the armed
clash, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
The wounded guard was sent to the Sirnak State Hospital, the
report added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces started large-scale operations to
capture the PKK members who escaped after the assault, said the
agency.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a group of the PKK members shot dead six persons
and wounded three others when they raided Dikbogaz village of
southeastern province of Siirt.
</P>
<P>
Khalil Attachi, leader of the PKK was quoted by a newspaper
as saying in Lebanon that his organization will attack Israeli
and U.S. targets in Turkish cities and tourist areas.
</P>
<P>
Attachi said that his group will "carry out operations
against Israeli targets in Istanbul (Turkey's largest city) and
elsewhere in Turkey and against U.S. enemy interests."
</P>
<P>
According to Turkish military sources, over 2,000 PKK
members have been killed since mid-May when the 50,000-strong
Turkish government troops intruded northern Iraq to attack the
PKK.
</P>
<P>
The PKK, the country's separatist group, has been fighting an
almost 13-year-old war for autonomy in eastern and southeastern
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
