<HEADLINE> Australia's Economic Growth Reaches Five-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Australia's annual economic growth
has slowed down to 2.4 percent for the 1996-97 fiscal year despite
an improved performance in the first three months of 1997, the
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said in a report released
today.
</P>
<P>
The growth was found to be 3.2 percent in a previous survey
conducted by the ABS.
</P>
<P>
The national economy grew by 0.9 percent in the first quarter
of this year over the previous quarter due to higher levels of
consumer demand, exports and investment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, net foreign debt rose by 0.4 percent in the year to
March 31, reaching 199.9 billion Australian dollars (152 billion
U.S. dollars), up 705 million Australian dollars (535.8 million
U.S. dollars) from the revised estimate for the previous three
months, according to the ABS.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard told the parliament today that
"growth in 1997-98 is expected to be consistent with the budget
estimate while growth in 1996-97 is likely to be 3 percent,"
putting him at odds with Treasurer Peter Costello who told
reporters he was confident of recording a higher growth rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
