<HEADLINE> Slump in Refugees, Immigrants to Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of refugees and
immigrants to Russia from the former Soviet republics fell
significantly last year, the head of the country's migration
service said today.
</P>
<P>
Some 670,000 refugees and immigrants from neighboring republics
were registered in 1996, down from an average of one million a
year since the disintegration of the Soviet Union in 1991, Tatiana
Regent, head of the Russian Migration Service, told Inter-fax News
Agency today.
</P>
<P>
She attributed the fall to Russia's sluggish economy. 
</P>
