<HEADLINE> Italy to Beef up Troop Presence in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Italy is to send more troops to
Albania ahead of the June 29 general election in the Balkan
country to protect polling stations, Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said today.
</P>
<P>
But he said the exact number of the reinforcement troops has
yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
Italy has contributed 2,500 soldiers to the U.N-authorized
6,500-strong Multinational Protection Force (MPF) stationed in
Albania to help protect the supply of aid and maintain law and
order in the country which plunged into chaos in February after
armed rebels took to the streets.
</P>
<P>
Other countries in the Italian-led eight-nation MPF may also be
invited to bolster their contingents, but Italy will go ahead with
its reinforcements regardless, diplomatic sources said.
</P>
<P>
"After the elections, which we want to be free, fair and
honest, the military presence will be swiftly wound up," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
He said he and Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta were making
arrangements for the short-term reinforcement to ensure security
at all polling stations in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Dini also said that a civil assistance program, including the
reconstruction of the police force and justice and administrative
systems in Albania, would be moved into high gear after the
elections.
</P>
<P>
"The whole international community is focused on this,
otherwise, Albania's instability risks destabilizing the
whole Balkan region even more," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Albania's elections are seen as a key step to end months of
violence in the country, which was triggered by the collapse of
popular pyramid savings schemes last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
