<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Inflation Drops to 28-year Low in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Italy's annual inflation dropped to
1.6 percent in May, the lowest in 28 years, the national
statistics bureau ISTAT said today.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in April on an annualized basis was 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
But prices rose by 0.3 percent between April and May, the
highest increase since last November.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate would have been still lower had it not
been for a rise in postal rates, ISTAT said.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has been falling for several months in a row due to a
series of austerity measures taken by the Italian government in a
bid to qualify for the single European currency to be launched on
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
ISTAT said the biggest price rises over the last 12 months were
in housing and related expenses, 4.0 percent, and in education,
3.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
