<HEADLINE> China, Kazakhstan to Jointly Develop Oil Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh Prime Minister Akezhan
Kazhegeldin congratulated the China National Petroleum Corporation
(CNPC) today on its winning bid in the international auction for a
stake in Kazakhstan's petroleum corporation.
</P>
<P>
CNPC beat off rivals from the United States and Russia in the
auction to buy a 60 percent share of Aktobemunajgaz.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan welcomes China's participation in the development of
its new oil fields, the prime minister told CNPC Vice President Wu
Yaowen.
</P>
<P>
He said prospects for cooperation between the two countries
were good.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that bilateral cooperation, which involved Kazakhstan
obtaining China's drilling technology and China obtaining
petroleum, would be beneficial for both countries.
</P>
<P>
Aktobemunajgaz, based in western Kazakhstan, has two oil fields
with reserves of 590 million tons of petroleum and 220 billion
cubic meters of gas.
</P>
<P>
With more than 300 million U.S. dollars of Chinese investment
and Chinese technology, Aktobemunajgaz, whose oil output was 2.60
million tons in 1996, will be able to almost double its annual oil
output, Chinese experts say. 
