<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Forces Repulse Taliban Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 4 (Xinhua) -- An overnight offensive by the
Afghan Islamic Taliban militia north of Kabul has been repulsed by
opposing forces loyal to Ahmad Masood, ousted former military
chief.
</P>
<P>
The strategic towns of Gulbarhar and Jabul Siraj, located about
80 and 77 kilometers north of Kabul respectively, were still in
the hands of Masood's forces, Afghan sources in Peshawar,
northwestern Pakistan, said today.
</P>
<P>
Masood's official spokesman claimed that 160 Taliban fighters
had been taken prisoner and 80 others killed during the fighting
in Kapisa Province to the south of Gulbahar, according to the
sources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the anti-Taliban alliance, which controls northern
Afghanistan, has also offered to host an international peace
conference in its Mazar-e-Sharif base to help end the war in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the Organization of the Islamic Conference
and Afghanistan's neighboring countries would all be invited to
participate, reports reaching here quoted a spokesman of the
alliance as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It has been announced by the United Islamic Front for
Salvation of Afghanistan (UIFSA) that a conference will be held to
work on a peaceful solution to the Afghan issue," the spokesman
declared.
</P>
<P>
The UIFSA was created two days ago to replace the previous
opposition Council for Defense of Afghanistan under ousted warlord
Abdul Rashid Dostum who fled the country after his key commander
Abdul Malik revolted against him on May 19.
</P>
<P>
The five factions that make up the new coalition are the
National Islamic Movement, former Defense Minister Ahmad Shah
Masood's forces, the Shiite Hezb-e-Wahdat, Hezb-e-Islami of former
Premier Gulbuddin Hekmatyar and a former mujahedeen grouping
headed by Pir Sayed Gailani.  
</P>
</TEXT>
