<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A number of Israeli defense contractors will
present new products at the Paris Air Show later this month,
reported The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Israel Aircraft Industries (IAI) will introduce the unmanned
Harpy anti-radar attack aerial vehicle in Paris, the first time
the system will be featured at the bi-annual air show. IAI
executives said the company has sold 200 million U.S. dollars
worth of the Harpy systems.
</P>
<P>
Another contractor that will participate in the air show,
Azimuth Ltd., is unveiling a new GPS (Global Positioning System)
-based direction finder system called Comet.
</P>
<P>
Executives said at a news conference Tuesday that the system,
connected to any fire control system, can be found by satellite in
any weather.
</P>
<P>
Azimuth also announced it will exhibit the LIGHT module, which
is designed for upgrading existing laser range-finders to acquire
data for artillery and to obtain field intelligence.
</P>
<P>
"The demands of the modern battlefield make the need for
improved target acquisition more and more urgent," Azimuth
International Marketing Manager Reuven Fuchs said. "LIGHT
represents a breakthrough in providing target data for critical
applications in the field."
</P>
<P>
Some 1,700 exhibitors from 50 countries are expected to
participate in the Paris Air Show this year, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey is to issue bonds worth of 1 billion German
Mark (about 578 million U.S. dollars) on the Euromark bond
market, the largest of its kind since 1993, local newspaper
Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
The bond issue, which has a five-year maturity, will be
carried out in cooperation with two banks, Commerzbank and
Westdeutsche Landesbank, State Minister Ufuk Soylemez was quoted
by the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Soylemez said that the upcoming transactions will probably be
realized with lower costs than the prediction by the Turkish
Treasury, which is in charge of the concrete operation.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Turkey's total bond issue on the international
capital markets has reached 1.35 billion dollars, according to
the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's economic growth rate in 1996 reached 5.2
percent, almost the same as in the past 3 years, Jordan Times
today quoted a study by the Amman Chamber of Industry as saying.
</P>
<P>
After several years of economic "recession" (1988-1991), the
Jordanian economy registered a 16 percent growth in 1992,
followed by an annual growth at a rate of some 6 percent in the
subsequent four years, indicated the study.
</P>
<P>
There is also a 35 percent rise in the country's foreign
reserves at the Central Bank of Jordan (CBJ) by the end of 1996
compared with the 1995 figures, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is now undergoing an International Monetary
Fund-structured economic reform program due to end in 1999. The
program is aimed at pushing through privatization in some areas
and developing Jordan's industry and foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN - Gulf state Bahrain will provide Jordan with some 4.9
million U.S. dollars worth of overhead cables for a 400-kilovolt
power linkage between Jordan and its neighbor Syria.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a contract to the effect on Tuesday while
Bahrain is holding its first ever industrial exhibition here in
Amman, which started on Monday, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
This contract is one of those to be finalized during the
exhibition, the state-run English daily said.
</P>
<P>
With the exhibition, Jordan hopes to reactivate a bilateral
trade agreement signed in 1995 and to strengthen trade ties with
Bahrain, a gateway to the markets of the Gulf Cooperation Council
member countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan stressed here Tuesday the need to forge
industrial integration with Bahrain, a Gulf state that can help
Jordan enter the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) member countries'
markets with its unique geographical location.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan expressed hope to reactivate a
bilateral trade agreement signed in 1995 and to strengthen trade
ties with Bahrain while meeting with a Bahraini delegation.
</P>
<P>
The delegation was here to establish joint ventures with Jordan
and hold a five-day exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Around 50 Bahraini industrial companies display their products
at the exhibition and expected to hammer out joint
Jordanian-Bahraini projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
