<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Palace Museum Buys Precious Letters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Palace Museum in Beijing paid
8.52 million yuan for five letters from the Northern Song Dynasty
(960-1127) and a calligraphic work from the Yuan Dynasty
(1271-1368) at the Hanhai spring auction last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The letters include the only copy of handwriting of Shi Jie, a
Northern Song minister famous for his upright and outspoken ways,
and the calligraphy is the work in existance of Yang Zun, a famous
Yuan Dynasty calligrapher.
</P>
<P>
The works were referred to as national treasures by Xu Bangda,
an expert on Chinese painting and calligraphy who is a research
fellow at the Palace Museum. He says that there are only a few
remaining calligraphic works from the Northern Song Dynasty,
especially those recording social life and people's thoughts at
that time.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the museum spent 18 million yuan on a Chinese
painting, "Shi Yong Tu", from the Northern Song Dynasty at the
Hanhai autumn auction, and a lot of money at the Guardian autumn
auction for a painting by Shi Tao, a famous artist of the early
Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
Last year, it bought a Chinese painting by Shen Zhou, a famous
artist of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644), at the Hanhai spring
auction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat, Mubarak Hold Talks in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak held
talks with visiting Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat at the presidential headquarters today in a bid to
propel the deadlocked Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
It was the second meeting between the two Arab leaders in two
weeks for continued consultations on the peace drive that stalled
in March when Israel began to build a new Jewish settlement in
disputed Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reviewed the outcome of Mubarak's political
adviser Osama al-Baz's shuttle visits in the past few days to the
Israeli capital of Tel Aviv and Gaza to break ice in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the result of the talks between Mubarak and
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in the Red Sea resort of
Sharm el-Sheikh last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"All parties in the Middle East will face a dramatic situation
if the peace drive collapsed," he warned during his stopover in
Nairobi of Kenya en route to Cairo from Harare, Zimbabwe, where he
attended the summit of the Organization of the African Unity.
</P>
<P>
The PNA leader said the settlement practices were illegal and
ran counter to the Washington Agreement which stipulated no
demographic or geographical changes be made during the
transitional period to any of the settlements including those in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also rejected Israeli charges of his government's
involvement in the execution of three Palestinian land dealers.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made their return to the negotiating
table conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary policy.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu refused to stop the new construction and
instead proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the
Jewish housing project.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, speaking in parliament Tuesday, voiced
conviction that negotiations with Palestinians could be resumed in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
But he is less sure about the Syrian track, saying that Israel
did not receive a response to the proposal to resume negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who reportedly is floating a five-point initiative to
narrow the Palestinian-Israeli difference, had hoped to bring
together Arafat and Netanyahu at a tripartite summit.
</P>
<P>
As part of intensified Egyptian mediation efforts, Baz left
here Tuesday for a four-day visit to Washington to brief the
U.S. administration on his several shuttle trips to the PNA and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office said the Egyptian efforts made "some
progress," but Palestinian sources said that Baz failed to get
the Israeli response to Palestinian demands.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that after the talks, Arafat joined the
plenary session of talks between Mubarak and visiting Saudi Crown
Prince, Deputy Premier and head of the National Guards, Abdallah
Ben Abdel-Aziz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
