<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM Returns from OAU Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
returned home today after leading Egypt's delegation to meetings
of the 33rd Organization of African Unity (OAU) Summit conference,
held in Harare, Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return, Moussa told reporters that the summit dealt
with Africa's pressing issues, including the situation in Sierra
Leone whose coup leaders failed to win recognition of the summit,
developments in the Democratic Republic of Congo and burgeoning
reconciliation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"The summit dealt with various African and international
issues, with particular focus on trade, economy and investment,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Moussa urged African leaders to consider Egypt's membership to
pan-African economic blocs at the first summit meeting of the
African Economic Community Tuesday, which was held on the sidelines
of the OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
He also called for solving the problem of Egypt's absence from
all sub-regional economic blocs.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is the only African country which is not a member at any
regional economic blocs in the continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has complained that it was denied access to these
economic groups despite its repeated requests.
</P>
<P>
Moussa will report to Mubarak on the summit and the African
Economic Community meeting as well as his contacts with African
leaders on the sidelines of the top-level contacts.
</P>
