<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Economic Outlook Favorable: Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economic outlook for
1997 is quite favorable and its economic growth should be close to
5.1 percent in 1997 and 5.2 percent in 1998, according to the
forecast released by the Hong Kong Forecaster for the 1997-98
Pacific Economic Outlook (PEO) today.
</P>
<P>
Ho Lok-sang, head of the Department of Economics and Director
of the Center for Public Policy Studies of Lingnan College in Hong
Kong, said at a press conference that the external environment is
favorable to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He said that "stable interest rates, faster economic growth of
out trading partners and relatively stable exchange rates point to
faster economic growth in Hong Kong in 1997 and a similar rate of
growth in 1998."
</P>
<P>
He expected that inflation would fall slightly while retail
sales are expected to continue to improve noticeably in 1997,
helped by improved confidence and a surge in tourists.
</P>
<P>
On the economic relations between Hong Kong and the Chinese
mainland, he said that as the Chinese mainland becomes more
attractive as a destination of foreign direct investment, Hong
Kong will stand to benefit.
</P>
<P>
Greater inter-flows of capital and labor, as well as goods and
services suggest continuing economic integration between the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region and the mainland, he said.
</P>
<P>
The PEO, one of the projects of the Pacific Economic
Cooperation Council, is an annual forecast of 22 Pacific Rim
economies including Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0107 </DOCNO>
