<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grounded Airbuses to Return to Service in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's flag carrier Cathay
Pacific announced today that testing and certification of
modifications to the Rolls-Royce 700 engine have taken place and
the airline's A330-300 aircraft fleet will progressively return to
service.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific suspended its A330-300 services on May 24 after
three inflight shutdowns and a fourth on a Dragonair A330 created
questions about the Rolls-Royce Trent 700 engine's reliability.
</P>
<P>
The announcement said the problem, which was due to
insufficient lubrication of a bearing in the engine's step-aside
gearbox, has been rectified and Cathay Pacific and regulatory
authorities are satisfied that the modification is completely
airworthy.
</P>
<P>
The first revenue service of the A330-300 with the modified
Trent 700 engines will take place tomorrow morning while the rest
of the fleet will return to service over the next week. It is
expected that the modifications will be completed by June 13.
</P>
<P>
A total of 192 flights have been canceled since the suspension
of services, according to the announcement.  
