<HEADLINE> A Large Biological Potash Fertilizer Plant Operational in Hebei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- One of the world's largest
biological potash fertilizer plants went into trial operation
recently in the city of Baoding in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the plant, valued at more than 30 million yuan
(3.6 million US dollars) and one of the country's major industrial
projects, was undertaken by the Microbiological Research Institute
of the Hebei Provincial Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The plant will develop an annual production capacity of 10,000
tons, which is urgently needed for the country's farming
production, a local source said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that some 22.67 million ha of arable land, or
60 percent of the country's total, is farmland lacking in potash.
</P>
<P>
The research institute began studying the industrialization of
biological potash fertilizer in 1984.
</P>
<P>
The microbiological potash fertilizer they produced was applied
to more than 30 varieties of crops in 27 provinces and autonomous
regions, proving to be highly effective in boosting yields, with
unit output rising by 15 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Their research and large-scale production of the potash
fertilizer has drawn worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
Experts and entrepreneurs from 13 countries in Asia, Europe,
Africa and the United States are negotiating with the plant on
cooperative plans in technical training and trading for the
potash. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
