<HEADLINE> Sweden's Early Membership in EMU Ruled out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Sweden will not seek to join the
European Union's single currency system when it starts in January
1999, Swedish Prime Minister Goeran Persson said late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Persson said it would be "provocative" to present parliament
with a proposal to join the monetary union this fall, when the
public support for the initiative is so weak. He also said that
the consequences of a single currency are still too uncertain.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that Sweden is not closing the door to a
Swedish membership in the future.
</P>
<P>
A special Social Democratic Party congress would be needed
prior to joining the EMU, as well as some type of general
election, such as a public referendum.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports here today, many Social Democrats
fear that participation in the EMU will reduce the government's
freedom to maintain a high level of taxation, which is necessary
to finance Sweden's extensive social welfare programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
