<HEADLINE> Johannesburg' Leading Hotel Shrinks Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A popular sense of insecurity
has badly affected business of leading hotels in commericial city
of Johannesburg, the industrial sources complained.
</P>
<P>
Perceptions of Johananesburg as crime ridden have forced
Holiday Inn Garden Court, one of the inner city's leading hotel,
to discontinue certain services because of lack of guests, the
hotel managing director Helder Pereira said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said his hotel had cut down to 250 rooms from its orgininal
800 as it was no longer attracting enough guests.
</P>
<P>
The glittering modern hotel was opened in 1986 as the
five-star Johannesburg Sun International. In 1993, it was
downgraded to a three-star hotel to adjust to the changing
inner-city market, and it became the Holdday Inn Garden Court.
</P>
<P>
Pereira said although criminal cases, especially robberies and
muggings have dropped remarkablly in the streets around the hotel
last year, "the perceptions of crime are still there."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that no four- or five-star hotels would survive in
central Johannesburg becuase there was no market for them
anymore. 
</P>
