<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Finds Cause for Female Panda's Curbed Sexuality (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The method was first tried in 1989 on a female giant panda
named "Qingqing," who was in heat irregularly.
</P>
<P>
The experiment worked, and Qingqing gave birth to a cub named
"Xingxing." Qingqing had three more sets of twins in the following
three years.
</P>
<P>
"This demonstrates that a proper supplement of external
gonadotrophins can adjust the giant panda's internal secretion for
reproduction, which will maintain its effectiveness in the
following years and increase the chances of producing twins," Chen
said.
</P>
<P>
"The low reproductive ability of the giant panda is the major
cause for the endangering of giant pandas," the Chinese researcher
said.
</P>
<P>
"Most female giant pandas cannot enter into periods of sexual
excitement easily or at least not obviously so during the mating
season," he noted. "Even if they succeed in mating, the pregnancy
rate is very low."
</P>
<P>
Researchers believe that only 10 percent of giant pandas are
able to mate naturally.
</P>
<P>
The research paper of Chen and his group has been published in
the latest English-edition of "Chinese Science Bulletin," the
leading scientific journal in China.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda, with a population of less than 1,000, is the
world's best-known endangered species. It can only be seen in
mountains in southwest and northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The female giant panda normally bears one or two cubs once a
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Find Cause for Female Panda's Curbed Sexuality (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Why does a female giant panda often
give the cold shoulder to her boyfriend?
</P>
<P>
Scientists have theorized her sexual arousal is curbed by a
disorder of the reproductive hormones -- a finding which has
solved one of the trickiest problems faced in the breeding of the
endangered species.
</P>
<P>
A research group of Chinese zoologists have discovered that the
reason behind the giant panda's low reproductive ability is her
lack of hormones during mating season.
</P>
<P>
"We found that the secretion of gonadotrophins, hormones which
support and stimulate the function and growth of reproductive
cells, determines the periodic sexual excitement of female
pandas," said Professor Chen Dayuan, head of the group, at the
Institute of Zoology under the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"When the female giant panda produces a sufficient secretion of
gonadotrophins, she will attain a state of sexual excitement; when
inadequate, she will show indifference to the male even in the
mating season," Chen explained.
</P>
<P>
The lack of this secretion makes it difficult for the female
giant panda to produce eggs, or for the fertilized eggs to enter
the uterus and grow and mature, he noted, pointing out that "this
will severely hinder the reproduction of the species."
</P>
<P>
To get to the root of the problem, the research group has
experimented with giving supplemental hormones to the female giant
panda, so as to stimulate her into a period of sexual excitement
and help her to produce eggs, and ensure that the fertilized eggs
can attach themselves to the uterine wall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 09:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Important Discoveries from Killer Quake in East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese and Iranian
seismologists discovered a big barrier lake and a
80-kilometer-long deformation and rupture zone after the killer
earthquake in east Iran last month, a Chinese specialist said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuanhu, Director of Earthquake Prediction and Prevention
Department of the China State Seismological Bureau, told Xinhua
that the joint research by the Chinese and Iranian seismologists
resulted in rare but important discoveries.
</P>
<P>
"The two discoveries from quake-stricken areas are of great
importance and high value to academic study in field of
seismology," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese specialist said that the seismologists of the two
countries are now making a comprehensive study on various kinds of
data obtained from the earthquake measured on 7.1 Richter scale on
May 10 and will make a prediction for the future quake development
in the area.
</P>
<P>
From May 24 to 31, a group of six Chinese specialists came to
Tehran and launched a joint research with 12 Iranian specialists
in Qaen and Birjand region, where about 2,000 people were killed
and thousands of others injured in the quake.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the deformation and rupture zone caused by the
quake is 80 km long with a direction from northwest to southeast.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of earth's surface deformation and rupture has been
rarely seen in the past and it is a typical case," he added.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, the displacement of shear of the
earth's surface is as wide as 2.8 meters in horizontal and
vertical displacement is as wide as 2.4 meters.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the Chinese and Iranian specialists also made
researches on type of house construction, destructive degrees and
damages inflicted by the killer quake, noting that the intensity
of the epicenter region was 10 degrees.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Reza Gheitanchi, head of Earthquake Seismology
Institute of Geophysics, Tehran University, told Xinhua earlier
that the cause for the killer quake is the Arabia plate on the
earth, which moved northward and collided with the stationary
Russia plate.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is being sandwitched between the two plates -- the
Arabia plate and the Russian plate. That is the cause of
the earthquake," said the Iranian seismologist.
</P>
<P>
The specialist analyzed that there are other two factors
leading to the strong earthquake. The Indian plate is also
moving northward to the Himalayas of China, thus causing lateral
pressure upon the eastern part of the Iranian plateau.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there is interaction in the eastern part of the
Iranian plateau due to direct and indirect forces generated by
the two moving plates. The Arabian plate is moving three
centimeters each year.
</P>
<P>
Gheitanchi said "We have earthquake belts in plate boundaries
such as the Zagros plate boundaries and the Alborz plate
boundaries. We have also many folds and faults inside the
Iranian plateau."
</P>
<P>
"There are also some local forces from the interaction of
these several forces. We have had several activities in the
past 30 years," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
