<HEADLINE> Beijing to Build Intelligent Transportation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China's State Science and
Technology Commission (SSTC) and the European Union (EU) will
cooperate to build an intelligent transportation system for
Beijing's ringroads, to ease chronic traffic jams in the Chinese
capital.
</P>
<P>
An official with the SSTC said today at the ongoing China-EU
International Symposium on Intelligent Transportation Systems
(ITS) that the project will be implemented by Beijing Municipal
Science and Technology Commission and Beijing Traffic Management
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
China will import key equipment for the building of the system
and introduce traffic management technology from EU countries and
the EU will be in charge of personnel training, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, SSTC Vice Minister, said today at the opening
ceremony of the three-day international symposium that he expected
to further Sino-EU cooperation in ITS fields.
</P>
<P>
The ITS computer, communication sciences, and other high
technology will be a major development trend of transportation in
the 21st century, Xu said.
</P>
<P>
Xu said China is attaching much attention to the development
and application of the ITS, viewing it a priority field for
transportation development.
</P>
<P>
The official said China could learn experience from the EU
countries in the ITS application.
</P>
<P>
Martin Bangemann, Commissioner of European Commission
responsible for industrial affairs, information and communication
technologies, said the EU will make more efforts on pushing
forward the China-EU cooperation on ITS fields.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 representatives from the EU countries and 140
Chinese representatives are attending the symposium. The
participants will seek ways for future cooperation on ITS research
and application. 
</P>
</TEXT>
