<HEADLINE> China's Forest Stock Keeps Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China's forest stock continues to
stay ahead of the country's consumption of forest resources, says
a report released here today by the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection (SBEP).
</P>
<P>
The latest report says that the country has a forest area of
133.7 million hectares, with the forest coverage rate up to 13.92
percent and the forest stock amounting to 11.7 billion cubic
meters.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China's total consumption of forest
resources was around 300 million cubic meters in 1995 and that of
bamboo was more than 490 million pieces.
</P>
<P>
The report, written by several ministries and commissions
including the SBEP and the Ministry of Forestry, reveals that
China afforested some 4.92 million hectares in 1996. A total of
535 million people were involved in voluntary tree-planting
activities, with 2.4 billion trees planted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the report says that 5,055 forest fires occurred
last year, with more than 186,000 hectares of forest area
affected. The rate forest area affected has decreased to less than
0.075 percent, keeping the rate to a record low level for nine
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the area of the forest affected by pest
disease has also decreased compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The 17-page report, divided into two parts, gives details about
the achievements that China scored in environmental protection
last year and the problems that still remain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
