<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, June 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS -- The European Union (EU) on Tuesday announced the
extension of its limited sanctions imposed on Nigeria for another
six months, local media reported today. The decision was taken by
EU foreign ministers at a meeting in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Former army Chief of Staff Ehud Barak was elected
today the new leader of Israel's opposition Labor party with a
resounding victory. After all votes in the Labor election held
Tuesday were counted just after midnight, Barak won 51 percent of
the vote. Speaking to Israel Radio after his sweeping victory,
Barak hailed the election as the first step by the Labor toward
returning to power.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Cooperation between the Inkatha Freedom Party
(IFP) and the Democratic Party (DP) would be enhanced,the two
opposition parties said in a joint statement. IFP and DP leaders
said their parties shared many politics, including a common
commitment to federalist. The IFP,representing the country's eight
million Zulu tribe population, is the biggest black opposition.
The DP is the white political party in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- A huge explosion rocked Kabul early today as an
ammunition dump of the Afghan Islamic Taliban militia went up in
smoke. The blast took place at the base of the historic Bala
Hissar fortress in east Kabul, which is a depot for munitions.
There were no immediate reports of casualties in the explosion.
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar are to submit their
inclusion list of products for the common effective preferential
tariffs (CEPT) scheme when they are admitted into the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in July, ASEAN Secretary
General Dato Ajit Singh said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Sri Lankan troops, resuming their operation "Jaya
Sikuru" (Certain Victory) after a six day pause were pushing
further into rebel-held territory in the North on Tuesday,
according to informed sources today. The sources said more rebel
targets come in for heavy attack by air force and artillery as the
troops were closing in on the heavily fortified rebel-controlled
Northern town of Puliyamkulam.
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- There is no winner or loser between Ukraine and Russia
following the signing of the three agreements on the Black Sea
Fleet last week, Ukraine Prime Minister Pavel Lazarenko said
Tuesday. Under the agreements, Russia will lease for 20 years
three bays of Sevastopol -- Sevastopolskaya, Yuzhnaya and
Karantynnaya -- as its naval base.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. administration's delay in expanding free
trade in Latin America was attacked today by both the Republican
and Democratic parties in the Senate. During a hearing of the
Senate Finance Committee, Democrats and Republicans complained
that the administration's delay was costing American companies and
workers who were losing out in the battle to expand markets in
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Tuesday that it decided
to support renewal of the U.N. oil-for-food deal for Iraq after
the agreement expires by June 7. U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan on Monday recommended the renewal of the deal on the same
terms: allowing Iraq to sell up to $2 billion worth oil for six
months and use use the money to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain and Ireland said Tuesday that IRA's political
wing Sinn Fein would not be allowed to the multi-party peace talks
unless IRA called a cease-fire. An aide to Irish Foreign Minister
Dick Spring told reporters in Belfast that the two governments'
patience was also running out. 
</P>
