<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze in Enviable Position for Industry Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Yangtze River will be in the
enviable position of having the world's largest riverside economic
belt along its valley, a Chinese researcher predicts.
</P>
<P>
The development of the Yangtze, which stretches for 6,400
kilometers and is the world's third longest river after the Nile
and the Amazon, can far exceed that of other large rivers in the
world, said Chen Wen, an associate research fellow with the
Nanjing Research Institute of Geography and Lakes of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar of the Young Scientists Forum recently
held in Beijing, Cai said that the Amazon claims the most water
resources of all rivers in the world and has a long navigation
channel on its mainstream. But the total length of the navigation
channels of its tributaries is far shorter than the Yangtze's.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the region which the Amazon traverses is overgrown
with tropical rainforests. Its valley is not considered for
large-scale development so that protection of the eco-system can
be ensured.
</P>
<P>
As for the Nile, most of it flows through dry areas and only
the river delta which has a "green corridor" has value for
economic development, she said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the Mississippi River in the United States, Chen
pointed out that the US focuses its economic development in its
eastern and western coasts and the Great Lakes area. It is only in
the past few decades that the country began to develop industries
along the middle and lower reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Europe's most prosperous riverside industrial belt is located
along the Rhine, but the river is only 1,400 km, far shorter than
the Yangtze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze in Enviable Position for Industrial Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Yangtze has geographical advantages, as it is the boundary
between China's northern and southern parts. In addition, water
and land resources are well-matched in the river reaches, leaving
a vast territory for development, she said.
</P>
<P>
Navigation channels of the Yangtze river system amount to an
unrivaled 70,000 km, extending to all parts of China. Furthermore,
long stretches of riverbanks and abundant hydropower resources of
the river remain to be developed.
</P>
<P>
Cai's views are shared by some 60 researchers from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and another eight departments which have
conducted a comprehensive study on the Yangtze since 1993. And
their scientific achievements are of "great value for reference,"
agreed mayors of the cities along the river.
</P>
<P>
So far, national-level agricultural and sideline products bases
have been set up in the Dongtinghu, Jianghan and Lixiahe plains.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an industrial corridor including the manufacturing
of mechanical products, electronics, automobiles has been set
up. And a heavy industry belt including Baoshan, Shanghai,
Maanshan, Wuhan and Panzhihua steel plants as well as a
petrochemical industry belt including Jinshan, Yangtze, Zhenhai
and Yueyang petrochemical firms have been formed.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River reaches have a solid economic foundation:
the GNP of the areas along the river comprises 40 percent of the
country's total. Of China's seven major groups of cities, three
are located in the reaches, including the Shanghai-Ningbo-Hangzhou
area, the Sichuan Basin and the Jianghan Plain.
</P>
<P>
Since New China was founded in 1949, investment priority has
been given to the areas along the Yangtze. Areas along the river
have been given unprecedented development opportunities and have
speeded up economic growth along with the construction of the
Pudong New Area in Shanghai and the gigantic Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, the average growth rate of the Gross Domestic
Product of seven provinces and Shanghai was only 0.5 percentage
points higher than the national level, while in the 1990s, the
rate is two percentage points higher.
</P>
<P>
In response to the country's strategy of developing Pudong and
the Yangtze, provinces and municipalities along the river have
shifted their economic focus to the areas along the river, setting
up a group of economic-technological areas and high-tech zones in
the river delta and the cities of Wuhan, Chongqing, Yichang,
Jiujiang, Yueyang.
</P>
<P>
Areas in the middle and upper reaches of the river are planning
to develop the Wanjiang and Chuanjiang rivers, and build several
industrial belts in Jiangxi and Hubei Provinces.
</P>
<P>
Cai said as long as the government heeds the development of
resources, the economy, and environmental protection, and offers
favorable policies, the riverside industrial belt along the
Yangtze will become the largest of its kind in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
