<HEADLINE> S.Africa Supports Resumption of Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG,June 4 (Xinhua) -- South African government would
not rescind its decision to support a resumption of ivory
trade,minister of Environment Pallo Jordan told parliament
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
A local daily Business Day today quoted him as saying that the
government made the decision because it was bound by the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) stand.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said his government would support a
resumption in legal trade in white rhino horn.
</P>
<P>
Jordan was reacting to a plea by a parliament committee for
cabinet to review its decision to press for legal trade in white
rhino horn and to support limited trading in ivory.
</P>
<P>
The South African parliament will debate on the issues.
</P>
<P>
The two issues are to be put in the form of proposals to next
week's meeting of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangeres Species in Harare,capital of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Animal welfare groups have warned that any relaxing of the
present complete bans on trade in elephant and white rhioceros
products would encourage poachers and could signal the death of
those animals remaining in certain African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
