<HEADLINE> Manila Prepares Former Rebels' Integration Into Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine National Police will
start screening this week members of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF) for integration into the police force, the Philippine
News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The screening of MNLF members for possible enlistment in the
police was suspended months ago after the authorities found out
that some applicants were not actual members of the MNLF.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the national police in Zamboanaga city,
Mindanao, was quoted by the agency as saying that a screening
committee has been created at the Zamboanaga Regional Police
Headquarters to go over documents certifying an applicant's
qualification for integration.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed between the government and the MNLF
last September to end a war in Mindanao, a total of 1,500 MNLF
members will be absorbed into the police force in Mindanao, and
5,000 MNLF members will be integrated into the government army.
</P>
<P>
While the national police is starting its screening of MNLF
members, the government army began the training of an initial 227
MNLF soldier candidates last Sunday. Over 1,000 MNLF members have
already passed qualification screening last March.
</P>
<P>
Similar trainings for other MNLF soldier candidates will be
held at training camps of the army divisions in Mindanao.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
