<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Third of Egypt's Public Sector Goes Private by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 30 percent of the public
sector companies will have been sold by the end of June as Egypt
picks up its pace of privatization.
</P>
<P>
Local daily the Egyptian Gazette today quoted Information
Minister Safwat el-Sheirf as saying 79 state-owned companies have
been sold and 10 more will go on sale this month, all these making
up 28.2 percent of the public enterprises sector.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark here Tuesday after Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri reviewed the performance of Egypt's privatization
program with the Ministerial Privatization Committee.
</P>
<P>
The committee will discuss the sales of 20 other companies till
the end of this year, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
At the Tuesday meeting, the committee approved the
restructuring of 50 companies in preparation for marketing them,
Sherif said.
</P>
<P>
Sherif also revealed decisions taken by the committee regarding
the privatization of big-weight state-owned factories.
</P>
<P>
The government has given green light to sell part of the shares
of Alexandria Millers Company, Egyptian Engineering Industries
Company and Arab International Contracting Company.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt has said that it has no plan for privatizing
the military factories.
</P>
<P>
"These factories and companies enjoy financial and
administrative regulations enabling them to work as successfully
as the private sector," said Minister of State for Military
Production Mohammad al-Ghamrawi Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The private sector took up 60 percent of the volume of economic
activities in Egypt by 1995, a 50 percent rise over the 1970s. The
sector is expected to shoulder 70 percent of the investments in
the coming years.
</P>
<P>
But the government has been reluctant to sell a majority stake
in vital sectors, such as oil and gas, telecommunications and
transports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
