<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Becoming Busy Air Service Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-two airlines from 17
countries and regions offer air service to Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The city is second only to Beijing in terms of international
air service in China.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai started its first international air route in 1964, but
saw little progress in international air service until the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
According to local air authorities, Hongqiao International
Airport of Shanghai now handles 230 planes from overseas air
companies each week, accounting for 11 percent of the airport's
weekly traffic.
</P>
<P>
The air authorities attributed the boom of the city's
international air service to Shanghai's sustained economic
development and opening-up of Pudong New Area in early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Many overseas airways have seen clearly business potential in
Shanghai, and started and increased regular air service or added
chartered, special air services to Shanghai in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
The Hongqiao Airport also handled 9,050 planes from overseas
airlines last year, which transported 1.45 million passengers and
some 90,000 tons of cargo and mail.
</P>
<P>
Local departments have worked hard to create sound conditions
for overseas airlines to operate more easily in Shanghai.
</P>
</TEXT>
