<HEADLINE> S. African Sugar Producers Expand Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOAHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's two major
sugar producer, Illovo Sugar and Tongaa-Hulett, are making active
efforts to expand business cooperation with Southern African
countries, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
The former has added operations in Malawi, Mauritius and
Swaziland to its existing interests in Mozambique and Kenya,
while the latter is active in Zimbabwe and Mozambique, and
looking to expand further in the region, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Illovo, South Africa's largest sugar producer, had acquired 50
percent of Mozambique's Maragra mill and the contract to mangage
the rehabilitation of a sugar mill in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, Tongaat is expanding its Triangle sugar mill, the
world's lowest cost producer, and plans a 59-million U.S. dollar
new sugar-making factory in the Mazoe Valley, 60 kms outside
Harare.
</P>
<P>
Tongaat has also singed an agreement with Tate and Lyle and
the Mazoe Valley growers to establish a 140,000 tons a year sugar
mill which is due to come on stream by May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Southern Africa, one of the world's lowest-cost producers of
sugar, is set to expand export capacity in the next few years.
The South African sugar manufacturers are likely to be at the
forefront of this thrust, the local industrial sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African region has an annual output of about four
million tons of sugar, of which it consumes about half and
exports the rest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
