<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged not to Overrely on Foreign Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has warned African countries not to overrely on foreign loans,
saying such funds have become an impediment to the development of
the whole continent, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Due to huge borrowing from foreign countries, Africa now is
heavily indebted and could not achieve any meaningful development
under such a burden, he noted at the summit of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) in Harare on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although currently most African countries are banking on
foreign investors, it is prudent to evolve home-grown economic
activities that are self-sustaining, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Moi also urged rich countries to alleviate the debt burden on
Africa, noting that despite the ravages of colonialism, Africa
has not benefited from any relief arrangements like U.S.'s
Marshall Plan in Europe after the World War Two. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
