<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State-owned Enterprises Discharge Less Pollutants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Pollutants discharged by China's
state-owned enterprises decreased last year, says a report
released recently by the State Bureau of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
The latest report says that of industrial waste emissions in
1996, the soot, ash and dust discharged by the state-owned
enterprises decreased by 9.5 percent and 12.1 percent compared to
the previous year, while their sulfur dioxide emissions stayed at
the same level.
</P>
<P>
The discharge of industrial waste water dropped by 7.2 percent
from 1995. The content of Chemical Oxygen Demand (COD) and heavy
metals in the discharged sewage decreased 8.4 percent and 14.3
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 660 million tons of industrial solid waste was
generated, up 20 million tons over 1995. But, the amount of the
industrial solid waste accumulated decreased by 150 million tons
to 6.49 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
The report revealed that with the fast growth of township
industries, their discharge of pollutants was on rapid rise.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the emission of sulfur dioxide, soot, ash
and dust from the country's township enterprises contributed to
28.2 percent, 54.2 percent and 68.3 percent, respectively, to the
country's total discharge of corresponding pollutants in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The generation of solid waste from the township factories
accounted for 38.6 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
The report also says that China completed 5,717 projects for
pollution control, and a total of 4.42 billion yuan (about 0.55
billion US dollars) was spent.
</P>
<P>
The 17-page report, divided into two parts, gives details about
the achievements that China scored in environmental protection
last year and the problems that still remain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Tea Production Falls Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenya produced 54,970 tons of tea
between January and April, a 41.17 percent drop compared with the
same period of last year, according to Mombasa-based Africa Tea
Brokers (ATB).
</P>
<P>
In a report issued here on Tuesday, ATB said that output for
April 1997 was 10,920 tons, a fall of 12,570 tons or 53.58
percent from April last year.
</P>
<P>
Last March, Musa Sang, Chairman of the Kenya Tea Growers
Association, predicted that Kenya's tea production was likely to
drop this year due to the prolonged drought.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the drought had caused damage to tea
bushes in the main growing districts.
</P>
<P>
At present, ATB report noted that most areas had recovered
from the severe drought and factories had now reverted to normal
production.
</P>
<P>
Rainfall has given way to longer periods of sunshine in Key
growing areas but temperatures remained low and growth is
inhibited, it added.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Kenya's tea production rose by 5.2 percent from
244,000 tons in 1995 to 257,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase was due to favourable weather conditions, timely
application of fertilizer and the improved prices.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, a leading tea producing country, last year exported a
record 244,000 tons of tea, overtaking Sri Lanka and India to
become the world's largest tea exporter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
