<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 07:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Elected New Labor Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Former army Chief of Staff Ehud
Barak was elected today the new leader of Israel's opposition
Labor party with a resounding victory.
</P>
<P>
After all votes in the Labor election held Tuesday were
counted just after midnight, Barak won 51 percent of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
He defeated comfortably three other candidates Yossi Beilin,
Shlomo Ben-Ami and Ephraim Sneh, who won 28 percent, 14 percent
and 6 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's election was in fact anti-climax, because Barak has
long been tipped to be the winner due to his prestige and
influence within the party.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israel Radio after his sweeping victory, Barak
hailed the election as the first step by the Labor toward
returning to power. The party was defeated just one year ago by
the Likud party led by current Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging the heavy responsibility placed upon his
shoulder by Labor voters, Barak said he would do his best to
replace the Netanyahu government in the future, either by
pushing for early elections or working to defeat Netanyahu in
the next elections in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Barak expressed confidence that, with this sweeping victory,
he was able to form an "active and combative opposition" to
challenge the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
He called upon other three candidates and all party members
to unite to face the challenge ahead. He said:"I believe that
together we can really create a kind of opposition that will put
a serious challenge to this government and will automatically
lead to the replacement (of it) by us."
</P>
<P>
Veteran Labor lawmaker Uzi Baram, a strong supporter for
Barak, agreed that "this is the first time in Labor's history that
such a clear, decisive victory was achieved. This will mean that
there will be no factions and no warring camps. We will defeat
(Netanyahu) in the next elections."
</P>
<P>
Outgoing leader Shimon Peres phoned Barak and congratulated
him on the victory. Barak said he would meet with Peres in the
next few days to complete the change of guard.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid, an ally of the Labor, also
congratulated Barak and expressed the hope that "your candidacy
at the head of Labor's ticket will help bring down this
government."
</P>
<P>
The turnout of Tuesday's election was nearly 72 percent of
166,000 eligible Labor voters, though it was markedly lower in
the cities. The voting was conducted peacefully in 6,662 polling
stations, with only minor complaints in the day.
</P>
<P>
Barak, 55, a former chief of staff and the most decorated
soldier in Israeli history, is widely regarded as the only
person within the Labor that could pose a strong challenge to
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Although he entered the political circle only two years ago,
Barak has served as interior minister and foreign Minister in
the previous Labor government under the slain premier Yitzhak
Rabin and Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
Due to the similar military background, Barak is often
compared to Rabin as a charismatic and popular leader. He is
described as having great personal capacities -- brilliant powers
of analysis and can deal with details and keep big picture in
front of him at the same time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
