<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 07:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Pays Lightning Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat arrived here early this morning for
further talks with President Hosni Mubarak on reviving the
deadlocked Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will review efforts to propel the peace process
and the outcome of talks Mubarak's Political Adviser Osama al-Baz
held recently in Gaza and Israel with the Palestinian and Israeli
sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Head of the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO)
Political Department Farouk Kadoumi, also flew here this morning
from Harare, Zimbabwe, to take part in the talks between Arafat
and Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
It is the second meeting between the two Arab leaders in two
weeks on continued consultations on the peace process that
collapsed in March when Israel began construction of a new Jewish
settlement in disputed Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's visist came a week after Mubarak met with Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu in Egyptian Red Sea resort of
Sharm el-Sheikh in a bid to break ice in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who reportedly is floating an initiative to narrow the
difference between the Israelis and Palestinians, had hoped to
bring together Arafat and Netanyahu at a tripartite summit.
</P>
<P>
But Arafat's spokesman said such a meeting would be meaningless
when Israel continues its settlement construction in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
As part of intensified Egyptian mediation efforts, Baz left
here Tuesday for a four-day visit to Washington to brief the
U.S. administration on his several recent shuttle trips to the PNA
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office said the Egyptian efforts made "some
progress," but Palestinian sources said that Baz failed to get
Israeli response to the Palestinians' demand.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have made their return to the negotiating
table conditional on a halt of Israel's expansionary policy.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has refused to stop the new construction and instead
proposed building a neighborhood for Arabs near the Jewish housing
project. He also proposed measures to ease the limitations against
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's five-point plan aimed at persuading the two sides to
the negotiating table includes a temporary halt of settlement
activities in Jerusalem and the West Bank and the resumption of
security cooperation between the PNA and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
