<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou to Accelerate Reform and Opening-Up Pace: Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Guizhou Province in southwest China
will speed up its reform and opening-up by firmly grabbing today's
opportunity, said Governor Wu Yixia.
</P>
<P>
The province will implement three strategies to build a
prosperous Guizhou with science and education, usher in fresh
development by opening wider to the outside world, and make
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The governor also pledged that they would intensify
construction of infrastructure and strive hard to create sound
conditions for overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou, one of the country's poorest regions, has now been
presented with the best opportunity for development, as the
central government has been paying unprecedented attention to the
situation of this backward Chinese province and has started to
implement the strategy of developing the central and western areas
of China at a faster pace, the governor explained.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu, the central government, various central
ministries and departments, will put some 10 billion yuan or about
1.2 billion US dollars to support Guizhou's farming and
poverty-relief work beginning from this year to the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
The province will be given preferential treatment in other
aspects including more approvals of major projects involving
infrastructure and energy development.
</P>
<P>
The central government has also listed Guizhou as one of key
provinces for development of resources during the Ninth
Five-Year-Plan Period (1996-2000) and will build three major
industrial bases along Wujiang River, in Liupanshui Prefecture,
and in areas along the Hongshui River, in a move to turn Guizhou
into an important energy and raw material center of south China.
</P>
<P>
The state will also invest to tap the province's plentiful
biological resources, developing green-food industries and
efficient farming in rural Guizhou.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of cooperation between coastal areas of the east
and western inland areas has also created chances for Guizhou's
economic development, and the province is advantageously located,
said the governor.
</P>
<P>
Four cities of Shenzhen, Qingdao, Ningbo, and Dalian have been
designated by the central government to help Guizhou and they have
signed agreements with Guizhou for economic cooperation over 100
projects, involving an investment of 1.87 billion yuan. Some of
these projects have already started construction or have been
ready for production.
</P>
<P>
Wu added that his province would invest 70 billion yuan in
building infrastructure from 1996 to 2000. With the operation of
Nanning-Kunming Railway Line, Guiyang-Zunyi Highway, and the new
airport of Guiyang, capital of Guizhou, this year, Guizhou will
also be adding 870 km of railway lines by the turn of this
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
