<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Powers Should Treat Each Other As Partners: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China hopes that in the process
of maintaining regional peace and prosperity, major powers would
learn to treat each other as partners, not as contenders, and no
one should try to seek a new rivalry where it is nonexistent, a
senior Chinese Foreign Ministry official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the first general meeting of the Council for
Security Cooperation in the Asia Pacific (CSCAP), Chen Jian,
Assistant Foreign Minister of China, said China places hope that
all the major powers will realize their responsibility to mankind.
</P>
<P>
"In the joint venture of maintaining regional peace and
prosperity, major powers would learn to treat each other as
partners, not as contenders. Nor should one try to seek a new
rivalry where it is nonexistent," he said.
</P>
<P>
The CSCAP was established by ten institutes of international
and strategic studies in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in July 1994 as a
non-governmental forum for multilateral security dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The founding CSCAP members represent institutes in Australia,
Canada, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia, New Zealand, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea, and Russia have since joined and in December 1996, China
and Vietnam were admitted as members.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Chen noted that the United States is a major
Pacific power, which is placed to make her unique contribution to
peace and prosperity of the region.
</P>
<P>
"We, in China, attach great importance to the role of the
United States and to a stable relationship with the United States
in the firm belief that such a relationship would not only benefit
our two peoples but would more over be conducive to peace and
prosperity in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
China is pleased to note that as a result of persistent efforts
by the parties concerned, Sino-US relations are moving in a right
direction, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This year has witnessed some important high level visits
between China and the United States. We are now preparing for the
exchange of state visits by the presidents of the two countries
that will take place later this year and next year," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the multi-polarization process of the world, the
Chinese official pointed out that one should not fail to see the
emergence of ASEAN (the Association of South Ease Asian Nations)
as a new power center and a significance force in Asia Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Noting that this year will witness the 30th anniversary of the
founding of the ASEAN and its enlargement from seven to ten
members, Chen said that it is of "vital importance" to China that
its relationship with the ASEAN is one of good neighborliness and
close cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"China highly commends and fully supports ASEAN's role in
promoting peace and development in the region. In this connection,
China is happy to attend the ASEAN plus three summit meeting," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
