<HEADLINE> Neolithic Relics Shown in East China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 relics, including an
ivory bird and China's oldest wooden spade, are on display in
Ningbo in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The exhibits were selected from over 1,000 relics unearthed
recently in Zishan which is part of the Hemudu site dating back
7,000 years.
</P>
<P>
The latest find suggests that Hemudu people used chopped chert.
</P>
<P>
Hemudu Culture, first found in Hemudu village in Yuyao in this
city in 1973, features rice cultivation, domestic animal keeping,
stone axes and chisels, and black pottery, etc.
</P>
<P>
A museum was built over the site, which has received some
250,000 visitors from at home and 55 countries and regions since
it opened in May 1993. The exhibition is being held in the
museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
