<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3-Phase Rupee Full Convertibility Suggested in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A special committee appointed by
the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) on capital account convertibility
(CAC) has recommended a three-phase rupee full convertibility in
three years' time.
</P>
<P>
In its 166-page report to the RBI governor in Bombay Tuesday,
the committee said that controls on capital outflows and inflows
must be liberalized in a phased manner and total interest
deregulation coupled with a transparent exchange rate policy will
facilitate full convertibility by 2000.
</P>
<P>
It has suggested that CAC may be implemented in three phases,
beginning this year.
</P>
<P>
The report said that over a period of time, capital controls
turned ineffective, costly and even distorting.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that along with further measures to liberalize
capital inflows, it was desirable to simultaneously liberalize
controls on outflows as a means of contending with capital
inflows.
</P>
<P>
In the context of large capital inflows, CAC would relieve
pressure on the exchange rate, the monetary aggregates and thereby
enhance the effectiveness of domestic policies.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the committee has put some preconditions or
signposts for CAC in the country such as reduction of both the
union and state governments' gross fiscal deficit, introduction of
a consolidated sinking fund, a system of fiscal transparency and
accountability, etc.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
