<HEADLINE> China-Made 100-Seat Airliners to Come Out by 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China will manufacture 100-seat
aircraft by 2003, the Aviation Industries of China (AVIC) has
announced.
</P>
<P>
A joint venture set up by the AVIC, the Science and Technology
Company of Singapore, and the AIA Company of Europe will turn out
105- and 125-seat airliners. The general assembly line will be in
China.
</P>
<P>
The AVIC holds 46 percent of the total shares of the Airbus
project; the AIA holds 39 percent; and the Singaporean enterprise,
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
European counterparts will provide technology and experience in
terms of engineering, production, quality inspection, and service,
AVIC said.
</P>
<P>
The project is an important step in AVIC's plan to manufacture
jet airliners by its own.
</P>
<P>
In line with practical situation, AVIC has tried a "three-step"
strategy:
</P>
<P>
-- to cooperatively produce MD planes, an effort to increase
manufacturing capacity;
</P>
<P>
-- to develop 100-seat airliners, as a breakthrough to produce
large domestic airliners; and
</P>
<P>
-- to manufacture large airliners with domestic technology.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country is expanding the production of MD-90
airliners, meaning the first-step plan is in full operation.
</P>
<P>
China is regarded as the largest potential aviation market in
the world. In the remaining years of this century, the country
will add 250 airliners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
