<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Primary School Students in the Hometown of Giant Panda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, Jane 4 (Xinhua) -- Every morning on the way to school,
11 year-old primary school student Li Lin passes a stone board
beside the road that says: "Not only humans need care and love."
</P>
<P>
She told Xinhua reporter how she understood these words: the
wildlife is the friend of mankind, they should be loved and cared
for so as to live for ever on the earth with humans.
</P>
<P>
Li Lin is a fourth-grade student in Yuanjiazhuang Primary
School in northwest China's Shaanxi province. Located in the
remote, thickly-forested Qinling Mountains, the school is near the
Foping National Nature Reserve where more than 60 giant pandas
live.
</P>
<P>
Tang Xiangyun, Li Lin's teacher, said that helped by the
reserve staff, the school often holds field trips, lectures and
contests, to raise the awareness of wildlife protection among kids.
</P>
<P>
"Our school students not only refrain from hurting wild animals
and birds, but also often persuade their parents not to shoot or
cut indiscriminately," the teacher said proudly.
</P>
<P>
In the school yard when asked "what do you know about the
giant panda?" a group of students, mostly between the age of ten
to twelve, answered immediately, with everybody eager to put in a
word.
</P>
<P>
"In our village, people call the giant panda the `black and
white bear'. It is one of the animals under top state protection,"
said one student.
</P>
<P>
"It is one of our `national treasures', eating bamboos and
bamboo shoots in the mountain," another student said, adding that
it is loved worldwide but only exists in China.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jing, a 12-year-old five-grade student, said that giant
pandas should be well protected, or this already threated animal
would dispear forever and people in the future would not have a
chance to see them.
</P>
<P>
"Our teachers told us that we should be proud of the Foping
National Reserve near us, and students in the hometown of giant
pandas should all become good models in protecting wildlife and a
clean environment," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to an administration head of the Foping National
Reserve, during the 18 years since the Reserve was established,
the number of giant pandas and other rare animals has been
maintained stable or even increased.
</P>
<P>
"Our reserve has been free of any serious fires during the 18
years, and two years ago our reserve was successfully selected by
the Ministry of Forestry and the Global Environment Facility as
one of the ten demonstration reserves nation-wide," he said,
stressing that the primary students nearby "have played a certain
role in publicizing and supervising the protection of wildlife".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Runs Household Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Li, an ethnic minority in south
China's Hainan province, have abandoned their primitive
slash-and-burn agriculture, and instead run modern household farms.
</P>
<P>
The Li nationality people in Nankun Township of Tunchang
County have established more than 100 household farms, which
cover up to 10 hectares each, said a local government official.
</P>
<P>
When Fu Ruxian became the first to put 100,000 yuan into
cultivating 10 hectares of wasteland for a household farm six
years ago, other villagers thought he was crazy.
</P>
<P>
But his prosperity convinced them, and more villagers adopted
his plan.
</P>
<P>
Farmers like Fu might start out without even knowing how to use
fertilizer, but they are learning about scientific farming and the
market economy, and changing their traditional extensive
cultivation to intensive operations with the help of the local
government and the Han people.
</P>
<P>
Fu Ruxian cultivated another 5 hectare of land for arecas and
tea-oil trees last year. He is doing long-term projects as well as
short-term ones, to avoid risks and earn better profits.
</P>
<P>
Less competent households are combining their efforts to open
farms, and running farms has become popular among the Li people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
