<HEADLINE> Navigation Freedom in South China Sea Ensured: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- China is "quite optimistic" that
peace and stability in the Asia Pacific region will be maintained
and freedom of navigation in the South China Sea will be ensured,
a senior Chinese Foreign Ministry official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the first general meeting of the Council for
Security Cooperation in the Asia Pacific (CSCAP), Chen Jian,
Assistant Foreign Minister of China, said that generally speaking,
the situation in the South China Sea is stable and with much at
stake, no one in the region will want to raise a rumpus.
</P>
<P>
Despite the probability that incidents might occur pending an
eventual solution to overlapping claims, Chen said, "With our
overriding common interest and given the political will, those
challenges are not impossible to meet."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the disputes in the region should be
resolved through peaceful means rather than by resorting to the
use or threat of force and, pending the eventual solution, parties
concerned should exercise utmost self-restraint and seek to shelve
the disputes and go for joint development.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the parties concerned shall place the
development of friendly bilateral relations at the top and not let
such disputes undermine their common endeavor for peace and
prosperity in the region.
</P>
<P>
"China has and will continue to follow these above-mentioned
principles," Chen said, adding, "with much at stake, no one in the
region will want to raise a rumpus."
</P>
<P>
The CSCAP was established by ten institutes of international
and strategic studies in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, in July 1994 as a
non-governmental forum for multilateral security dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The founding CSCAP members represent institutes in Australia,
Canada, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia, New Zealand, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea, and Russia have since joined and in December 1996, China
and Vietnam were admitted as members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
