<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Reactor to Be Built in Central Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's first research nuclear
reactor will be built in its central province of Nakhon Nayok, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet has approved the project recently, but the
construction of the nuclear reactor could not start as a legal
procedure on nuclear safety for the project has not been passed.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's nuclear safety regulations require any investors in
a nuclear project to submit a safety analysis report certified by
the United States Nuclear Regulations Commission (USNRC).
</P>
<P>
Yet, General Atomic, a U.S. company that won the bidding for
the project has not yet submitted such a report to the Nuclear
Safety Sub-committee of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Kriangsak Phattharakhom, secretary-general of the Office of
Atomic Energy for Peace, said that the cabinet approval of the
project and the safety requirement were different matters, and the
bid winner will have to clear safety hurdles itself.
</P>
<P>
The office earlier had proposed that the Nuclear Safety
Sub-committee drop its requirement for a safety report certified
by the USNRC, saying that Thai nuclear personnel were good enough
to certify the safety of a nuclear project themselves.
</P>
<P>
However, the sub-committee rejected the proposal, arguing the
expertise of Thai officials were not strong enough.  
</P>
</TEXT>
