<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Sets Budget Deficit Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria has decided to limit this
year's budget deficit to an equivalent of 6.2 percent of the gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the targets agreed upon between Finance Minister
Muravei Radev and An Makgark, the Bulgaria representative of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference today after their talks, the two
officials explained that the target is higher than planned because
the government will have no additional revenues to cover the
spending due to the stagnation of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
As the possibility to cover deficit with new borrowing has been
ruled out, Bulgaria will have to depend on the proceeds from
privatization for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Under a draft budget, the inflation rate at the end of this
year will be 566 percent and that for the entire fiscal year will
reach 1059 percent.
</P>
<P>
IMF has paid its first loan of 160 million U.S. dollars to
Bulgaria this year and, if the country has fulfilled all its
obligations, will soon pay two additional loans of 130 million and
86 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the World Bank is expected to provide a loan
of 80 million dollars for restructuring the economy and reducing
the unemployment rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
