<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar Looking to Join AFTA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar are to
submit their inclusion list of products for the common effective
preferential tariffs (CEPT) scheme when they are admitted into the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in July, ASEAN
Secretary General Dato Ajit Singh said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The presentation of the CEPT inclusion list is one of the first
steps taken to join the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA).
</P>
<P>
"As a result of the very close contact and assistance we at the
secretariat have been giving, we have helped them to draft the
initial package offer for the CEPT products," officials at the
ASEAN Secretariat today quoted Singh as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the three countries had already submitted an indicative
inclusion list to ASEAN senior economic officials in April.
</P>
<P>
"They are supposed to give us the final inclusion list on the
day they join ASEAN," he added.
</P>
<P>
At present, ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The CEPT is the main instrument designed to make ASEAN a free
trade area by 2003. Through the scheme, tariffs of all
manufactured goods will be reduced to 5 percent or less.
Agricultural products are excluded from the CEPT scheme.
</P>
<P>
Under the CEPT scheme, each ASEAN member draws up a product
list whereby goods are divided into: exclusion list, temporary
list and the general exception list.
</P>
<P>
According to Singh, the prospective members have decided to
submit the final product list at the 29th ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting in October.
</P>
<P>
As new members, Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar have a 10-year grace
period starting in 1998 before they are fully integrated into AFTA
in 2008.
</P>
<P>
All three countries are currently doing their utmost to meet
these requirements, Singh said.
</P>
<P>
Singh also confirmed that a meeting of ASEAN economic ministers
will be held in Jakarta next week.
</P>
<P>
The special half-day meeting was called to draft an economic
vision for the grouping in the next century, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
