<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Plans Agitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition party has
decided to launch protest programs across the country later this
month against the alleged irregularities by the government during
the recent local elections, sources here said today.
</P>
<P>
The decision came out Tuesday at the end of a three-day meeting
of the Nepali Congress (NC) party's Central Working Committee
(CWC), which was held here in the wake of the party's debacle in
the last month's local polls.
</P>
<P>
Election results declared so far show that the NC party has
lost its majority control of the country's over 4,000 local
administration bodies at village, municipality and district levels
to the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML), the biggest partner of Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur
Chand's ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
NC leaders at the CWC meeting vehemently accused the government
of carrying out irregular activities during the local elections to
give advantage to the major ruling party, according to party
sources.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to hold protest rallies and mass meetings
in all the 75 districts of the country simultaneously on June 15,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NC party has formed a special committee to
collect comprehensive facts and statistics about the alleged
election irregularities by ruling party workers.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that some NC activists on Monday picketed
the party central office, demanding the resignation of party
president Girija Prasad Koirala as he failed to lead the party to
retain its majority control at local levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
