<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Push Further Into Rebel Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan troops, resuming their
operation "Jaya Sikuru" (Certain Victory) after a six day pause
were pushing further into rebel-held territory in the North on
Tuesday, according to informed sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said more rebel targets come in for heavy attack by
 air force and artillery as the troops were closing in on the
heavily fortified rebel-controlled Northern town of Puliyamkulam.
</P>
<P>
Air force jets attacked four identified rebel targets while the
army had attacked six others in the past day.
</P>
<P>
According to a military report, while troops continue to
strengthen defenses in the newly recaptured areas, terrorists in
small groups are attempting to infiltrate to carry out
reconnaissance missions, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have meanwhile accused the government of firing
artillery on villages killing many and rendering thousands of
civilians homeless.
</P>
<P>
The government troops launched Operation Jaya Sikuru on May 13
using two army divisions consisting of about 20,000 in a bid to
open a supply route to Jaffna Peninsula by recapturing 75
kilometers of highway running through LTTE held territory.
</P>
<P>
The troops had earlier recaptured and consolidated defenses in
Omanthai and Nedunkeni which were held by the rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) fighting for a separate
state in the country.  
</P>
