<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Ruling Party Remains Leading in Vote Tally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's ruling party Golkar
remains leading in the vote tally from all 27 provinces in the
country, the General Election Institute (lpu) said today.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results of the election vote counting until 18:19
Tuesday showed Golkar won 82,983,276 votes of the total of 111.6
million votes counted, the United Development Party (PPP)
25,262,571 and the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) 3,421,470.
</P>
<P>
About 124.7 million Indonesians were eligible to vote in the
May 29 general election.
</P>
<P>
Based on these figures it was predicted Golkar would get 325
seats, PPP 90 and PDI 10 in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
PPP, Golkar and PDI are vying for 425 of the 500 seats in the
House of Representatives. The rest 75 seats will go to the Armed
Forces whose members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
The 500 members of the House of Representatives along with 500
nominated members will form the People's Consultative Assembly
that will among other things choose the country's next president
and vice president in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The lpu plans to conclude vote counting late today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
