<HEADLINE> BSECO, Mercosur to Develop Cooperative Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Black Sea Economic
Cooperation Organization (BSECO) and the South American Common
Market (Mercosur) will develop cooperative relations in the
future, said Romanian Foreign Ministry spokesman on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after a two-day seminar named "the
Cooperative Prospect between BSECO and Mercosur," which began on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, representatives from member nations of the
two organizations discussed the possibility of cooperation in many
fields such as trade, transportation and finance. Many said that
the two regions have complementary economies.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Foreign Minister Adrian Severin stressed at the
closing ceremony the importance for the two organizations to
conduct exchanges in economy, society and culture, saying that
Romania would become a "bridge" for future cooperation.
</P>
<P>
BSECO, which was founded in June 1992, is made up of 11
countries around or near the Black Sea -- Turkey, Bulgaria,
Romania, Greece, Moldova, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Georgia, Russia,
Ukraine and Albania.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, becoming operative in January 1995, consists of four
South American countries, which are Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and
Paraguay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
