<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Rebukes U.S. for Poll Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
rebuked the U.S. State Department for its remarks about the
Indonesian general election, calling them "inappropriate".
</P>
<P>
"I've read the statement by the U.S. State Department
spokesman, and I think it showed ignorance or lack of
understanding of out system," Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian minister expressed his regret over the U.S.
statement, saying that it showed lack of appreciation about what
Indonesians have been trying to develop with its democracy.
</P>
<P>
"I expected foreigners to at least try to understand that there
are different kinds of democracy, and any evaluation must be based
on an appropriate knowledge of the system," he added.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman John Dinger described the
Indonesian electoral system Friday as so tightly controlled by the
government that it "severely limits political competition".
</P>
<P>
Calling on the Indonesian government to investigate allegations
of vote-rigging and cheating, Dinger said in Washington: "more
broadly, we also believe Indonesia should move toward a political
system in which the will of the people can be heard."
</P>
<P>
The May 29 general election gave an overwhelming victory to the
dominant party Golkar, which won over 74 percent of the votes. The
United Development Party (PPP) obtained 23 percent and the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) 3 percent, according to figures
released by the National Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
Based on the provisional results, Golkar is expected to win 325
of the 425 seats in the House of Representatives that were up for
grabs, PPP 90 and PDI 10.
</P>
<P>
About 124.7 million Indonesians were eligible to vote in the
election, the sixth one in the country since 1971.  
</P>
</TEXT>
