<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Company Wins Bid for Venezuelan Oil Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese oil company today beat 11
other companies in contending a bid to explore an oil field on the
northern coastal area of Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
China's National Petroleum Corporation offered 118 million
U.S. dollars for 20 years of operation in the 39-square-kilometer
field in Intercampo norte, near the northwestern coast of Lake
Maracaibo in the state of Zulia.
</P>
<P>
The field, producing 6,700 barrels of crude oil a day from 59
active wells, was one of the 20 mature oil fields put up for
tender by Petroleos de Venezuela and the Venezuelan Ministry of
Energy and Mines.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese company is obliged to invest a minimum of 24
million dollars during the next three years, including
rehabilitation and work in all existing wells and installations,
drilling of new wells and other exploratory activities.
</P>
<P>
The field was discovered in 1954 and has produced a total of
178 million barrels of petroleum to date.
</P>
<P>
About 130 investors, domestic and overseas, are bidding for 20
mature oil fields. Bidding ends on June 6. The program, which is
estimated at six billion dollars, was initiated last November.
</P>
</TEXT>
