<HEADLINE> Italy to Denominate Debt in Single Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Italy will immediately denominate its
debt in the single European currency when the euro is launched on
January 1, 1999, the ANSA news agency quoted government officials
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Italian cabinet passed a bill today mandating the
government to introduce the single European currency.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi said Italy's immediate
conversion of the debt into euro "will help to create a critical
mass of the currency on the market, creating confidence that will
enhance the system's credibility."
</P>
<P>
He said: "The government has been conscious from the beginning
that participation in the single currency is in the national
interest and that any suggestion of a postponement runs against
the interests of Italy and of Europe."
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Romano Prodi said the euro mandate bill means
business. It was far "more than a formal measure".
</P>
<P>
The provisions of the bill also include the denomination of
stock and other markets in euro, and the calculation and payment
of business taxes in the single currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
