<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slaney Seeks USOC Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Mary Slaney and two other
athletes suspended for doping have appealed to the US Olympic
Committee to win a berth at the World Athletics Championships.
</P>
<P>
"They want us to help resolve the issue," said USOC executive
director Dick Schultz.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, world athletics governing body IAAF said it was
suspending Slaney, Sandra Farmer-Patrick and a third undisclosed
US athlete believed to be hurdler Stephon Flenoy because USA Track
and Field failed to promptly resolve cases against them.
</P>
<P>
That will deny them a chance to compete in the US national
championships next week in Indianapolis -- the qualifying meet for
the world championships at Athens in August.
</P>
<P>
Slaney, Flenoy and Farmer-Patrick purportedly tested positive
at last year's US Olympic trials but were allowed to compete in
the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
"It's strange the IAAF would suspend them without giving them a
hearing," Schultz said. "I don't know what their rationale was."
</P>
<P>
Flenoy and Patrick-Farmer contacted the USOC and asked for
reinstatement in time to compete at the US nationals. Slaney made
a written complaint to the USOC seeking a hearing by Friday so she
can compete at Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
US officials had results that showed Slaney with a
higher-than-allowed level of male hormones in her body at last
year's US Olympic trials, but allowed her to compete at the
Atlanta Games and in meets since.
</P>
<P>
While US officials delayed any hearing or action against her,
Slaney passed six later tests for the masking agent and said her
high male hormone ratio came from natural causes.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old Slaney is a four-time Olympian who made a
surprising comeback merely to reach the Atlanta Games. Jamaica
born Farmer-Patrick, 35, is a former US 400-meters record-holder.
</P>
<P>
Slaney will not go to court and fight for the right to compete
in next week's US meet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
