<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The creation of a single currency and one common
passport for Mercosur countries "is the natural evolution of
integration," Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, told
Argentine senators on May 26.
</P>
<P>
It will be up to the economic authorities of the four member
countries of the Mercosur: Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay, to decide when it is time to establish a timetable to
implement the two above-mentioned proposals made by Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- If the index rates of agricultural trade
balance continue to grow as they are doing now, exports by the
agricultural and livestock sector in Brazil will exceed 20 billion
dollars by the end of 1997, an increase of 11 percent compared
with that of last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of this year, exports of animal and
vegetable products increased 12 percent compared with the same
period in 1996, to reach the sum of 3.59 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, this South American country exported 17.9 billion
dollars worth of more than 35 animal and vegetable products.
</P>
<P>
ASUNCION -- The interior ministers for Argentina, Brazil,
Paraguay, Uruguay and Chile met on May 30 and 31 in Asuncion
to analyze common strategies designed to prevent international
organized crimed.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed on the need to give a "transnational
response" to "transnationalistic crime", maintaining that to
combat globalized crime, national police forces should not
concern themselves solely with internal matters but act in a
conjoined way with their counterparts from other nations.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil's gross domestic product (GDP) will
grow 4 percent this year compared with 1996, according to the
Institute of Applied Economic Research (IPEA).
</P>
<P>
Between January-March 1996, the GDP grew 4.2 percent over the
same period last year and the economy will maintain its growth
over the next few quarters, pointed out the IPEA in a report
published by the press on May 28.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics
calculates that the GDP will grow a maximum of 1.5 percent this
year compared with 1996 when it increased 3.2 percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuelan, Colombia and Ecuadoran businessmen
established the basic guidelines of what they believe should be
the Andean Community's strategy for integrating with the
Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting held May 25 and 26, they reaffirmed their support
to go ahead with the negotiations with the Mercosur and other
negotiations with the Caribbean, Central America and the Latin
American Integration Association (ALADI).
</P>
<P>
As for the deadline for complying with the tariff-elimination
program between the Andean Community and the Mercosur, the
businessmen believe a 10-year period is a prudent length of
time for non sensitive products and 15, 18 and 20-year periods
for more sensitive products. (to be continued)


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
