<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Warn of Breakdown of Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
insistence on deploying more troops to a controversial area in the
south could result in the breakdown of peace talks with Muslim
rebels, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Al-Haj Murad, vice chair for military affairs of the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), said a major reason for the
slowdown in the talks was the military continuing "encroachment"
on MILF's stronghold in Buldon, Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MILF have held four rounds of
preliminary talks so far but did not achieve any substantial
results. They are scheduled to hold the fifth round of
negotiations next month. The government wants to forge a
comprehensive ceasefire agreement with the rebels as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"Now they have plans to deploy more soldiers in Buldon to
secure Mayor Macarampat Manalao," said Murad, adding that more
deployment of troops in the highly sensitive area would threaten
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Government chief negotiator Fortunato Abat said earlier that
the military will send more soldiers to Buldon to install Manalao,
who has not been going to his office since being elected in 1995
because of what he claimed as threats from the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Buldon is a military headquarters of the MILF, a splinter
faction of the mainstream Moro National Liberation Front which
signed a final peace agreement with the government last year.
</P>
<P>
With 12,000 members, the MILF proclaimed itself the biggest
rebel group in the country. It has had a number of clashes with
government troops near Buldon since the beginning of the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
