<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Increasing Farmland By Removing Brick Kilns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 4 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
has recovered nearly 10,000 hectares of farmland in the past two
years by tearing down brick kilns that were violating land-use
regulations.
</P>
<P>
It has removed 1,134 kilns in the process, as part of an
attempt to increase grain production by five billion kg at the end
of the century, by increasing the amount of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The province has more than 6,000 kilns, occupying a total of
30,000 ha of arable land. The amount of earth used for bricks
annually eats up more than 5,000 ha of land, 70 percent of which
is fertile farmland. Per-capita land area has fallen to slightly
more than one-tenth of a hectare.
</P>
<P>
Brick and tile production has become a major industry in the
economic development of townships and villages, but the problem is
how to get good economic returns without damaging the farmland, a
provincial official said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with State requirements, the province has begun
to tighten controls on land-use, requiring land-use permits, and
improving reclamation of brick kiln-occupied land.
</P>
<P>
Hebei is also making an effort to replace bricks made of earth
with new building materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
