<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The seminar for Uruguayan businessmen on "How to
DO business with Brazil" was held on June 3 with the participation
of Minister of Industry, Energy and Mining Minister Julio Herrera
at its inauguration.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by the Uruguayan-Brazilian Chamber of
Commerce, helped Uruguayan businessmen learn about the
characteristics of the Brazilian market as both supplier and
recipient of products and services.
</P>
<P>
Technicians (Officials?) from these two countries presented
papers on the existing norms in matters of commerce, taxes,
transportation, financing, documentation, insurance and the
promotion of businesses.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguayan and Spanish delegations evaluated
on June 2 the plans of cooperation between both countries
countries in different areas.
</P>
<P>
The analysis will be made by followup, evaluation and planning
committees for the Spanish-Uruguayan Scientific, Technical,
Cultural and Educational Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The "Eco America 97" summit will be held in
Montevideo between August 26-29 with the participation of the four
Mercosur presidents and the environmental delegations from the 22
members nations of the Latin American Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The forum's objective is to analyze the processes on
sustainable development in Latin America and the successful
experiences and their potential adaptation to the reality of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Several initiatives designed to conserve the natural
environment will be brought up and a call will be made to
recognize the environmental impacts and the pollution generated by
several manufacturing activities.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- On June 10 the Mercosur will have its first
official contact with Peru, a country that abandoned the Andean
Pact and hopes to join this bloc, said Agustin Espinsosa, the
chief of Uruguay's Foreign Ministry Integration and Mercosur
Division.
</P>
<P>
Both sides will begin the negotiations that could lead to the
establishment of the characteristics of a free trade agreement,
starting with the basic criteria for trade, a timetable for
freeing trade and the norms that will be established for future
relations.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- On May 30, the Chamber of Argentine Exporters
(CERA), asked that the other three Mercosur countries be excluded
from the control imposed on the origin of Argentine imports that
Carlos Menem's government will apply to prevent tariff frauds.
</P>
<P>
The Cera sustains that this control, that will be granted to
private companies, violates the agreements signed by the four
country partners of the Mercosur Tariff Union.
</P>
<P>
"The non-exclusion of Mercosur partners will make trade
difficult due to an administrative stumbling block, which is
prohibited by existing agreements," pointed out Cera President
Enrique Mantilla. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
