<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- A seminar on the outlook of cooperation
between the member countries of the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) and the zone of cooperation of the Black Sea was
held in June 2-4 in Bucharest, Romania.
</P>
<P>
During the seminar, experts discussed topics related to
concrete modes of cooperation in matters of trade, duty-free
zones, complementarity of the economies of both blocs, ocean
and river transportation, as well as investments.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- On May 28, the government of Brazil announced
in Sao Paulo the elimination of the need for previous
authorization for the importation of Argentine lubricants to
Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation of this restriction constitutes a new advance
in the framework of cooperation and integration between the
two countries, according to Argentina's Deputy Foreign Minister
Andres Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Trade between Brazil and Argentina will
reach 14 billion dollars this year, an increase of 17.6 percent
over 1996, according to Brazil's Industry, Commerce and Tourism
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Argentine exports to Brazil increased 15.3 percent between
January-March and imports 23.4 percent, compared with the same
period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Argentina had a 260 million-dollar trade surplus with Brazil
for the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The Banco de la Nacion Argentina (BNA) and
the Banco DO Brazil (BB) recently signed an agreement to
swap lines of credit for 100 million dollars to guarantee
the flow of trade between the two countries, according to a
communique released by the latter to BNA.
</P>
<P>
In the first stage, the agreement will extend 50 million
dollars of loans to Argentine companies that export to Brazil.
(to be continued)

