<HEADLINE> Opposition Forces Form New Alliance Against Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's anti-Taliban forces
have formed a new alliance in a bid to check the Islamic militia's
taking over of the whole country.
</P>
<P>
The new alliance, named the United Islamic Front for Salvation
of Afghanistan (UIFSA), includes the National Islamic Movement,
former defense minister Ahmad Shah Masood's forces, the Shiite
Hezb-i-Wahdat, the Hezb-i-Islami of former premier Gulbuddin
Hekmatyar and a former Mujahedeen faction headed by Pir Sayed
Gailani, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The UIFSA was ready to hold talks with the Taliban, who control
two-thirds of the Afghan territory, the reports quoted an
opposition spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The UIFSA replaces the previous opposition coalition Council
for Defense of Afghanistan under ousted warlord Abdul Rashid
Dostum who fled Afghanistan after his key commander Abdul Malik
revolted against him last month.
</P>
<P>
Malik helped the Taliban to enter Mazar-i-Sharif but four days
later, turned against the Islamic militia, forcing it out of the
city after heaving fighting that left hundreds of fighters dead.
</P>
<P>
He has assumed leadership of the National Islamic Movement
which was led by Dostum before his flight.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Front replaces the earlier anti-Taliban alliance
that did not include Hekmatyar and Gailani.  
</P>
</TEXT>
