<HEADLINE> Ireland's Main Opposition Party Supports EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's main opposition Fianna
Fail party, which is tipped to win the Irish general election to
be held on Friday, has expressed its firm commitment to joining
the European Monetary Union (EMU) on January 1 1999, press reports
from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Dublin today, Fianna Fail
leader Bertie Ahern said: "The principle of joining EMU in the
first wave should not, I believe, be an issue. If we fulfill the
Maastricht criteria, which we do, we are legally committed to
becoming members."
</P>
<P>
"It would send very wrong signals to Europe, and would suggest
that we were to all intents and purposes an economic satellite of
Britain if we were to seek to renege on our commitment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on warnings by some economists that joining EMU
would be dangerous for Ireland's economy if Britain stayed out,
Ahern stressed that Ireland should be in the first wave whatever
Britain did.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition leader noted that there are strong
signs that Britain would join the single European currency.
</P>
<P>
"It is reasonably clear that the new British government are
preparing the ground for participation in EMU. Whether to begin
with or later is not yet clear," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the EMU timetable, Ahern expressed his convictions that the
EMU would go ahead on schedule, despite a landslide victory for
the socialist party in France's elections and a row between the
German government and Bundesbank over the revaluation of gold
reserves.
</P>
<P>
"There is in Europe a huge political commitment to EMU. I think
it is a mistake to read recent political upheavals and controversy
in France and Germany as meaning that it could all be about to
unravel," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
