<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Index in April Edges Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Leading Economic Indicators in
April decreased by 0.1 percent to 103.5, according to a
preliminary estimates by the New York-based Conference Board
today.
</P>
<P>
The leading index increased 0.2 percent in March, an upward
revision and highest in history. It increased 0.5 percent in
February, the research group said. During the six-month period
through April, eight of the ten leading economic indicators
advanced.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board's calculations show that six of the ten
leading economic indicators fell in April. The most significant
decrease is the average weekly initial claims for state
unemployment insurance.
</P>
<P>
The index is the key element in an analytic system designed to
signal peaks and troughs in the business cycle.
</P>
<P>
The data of April reinforced hopes that economic growth will be
modest enough to keep inflationary pressures tame without another
boost in interest rates by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
Bonds and other fixed-income investments are more appealing
when there's little threat of rapid inflation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
