<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Administration Criticized on Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration's delay
in expanding free trade in Latin America was attacked today by
both the Republican and Democratic parties in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
During a hearing of the Senate Finance Committee, Democrats and
Republicans complained that the administration's delay was costing
American companies and workers who were losing out in the battle
to expand markets in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
William Roth, chairman of the committee, said he was
disappointed with President Bill Clinton's decision to wait until
September to ask Congress for the authority he needs to negotiate
to expand the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
"I think that by delaying action until the fall, the president
runs the risk that we will not be able to complete `fast track'
this year or next," said Roth.
</P>
<P>
The fast-track authority legislation bars congressional
amendments to any trade agreements the administration negotiates.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has said he wants the authority to negotiate labor and
environmental agreements as part of any overall free trade deals,
but Republicans are opposed.
</P>
<P>
The Republicans argue that issues like labor and environment
are not directly related to trade and should not be part of
fast-track legislation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the hearing, U.S. Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky said that the delay had been a unanimous
recommendation from the Cabinet to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
She added that the administration was likely to seek broad
fast-track authority that would allow negotiations to go forward
with a number of countries over free trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and 33 other Western Hemisphere leaders in 1994 set
2005 as a target date for creating a hemisphere-wide free trade
area.
</P>
<P>
Barshefsky also told the senators that in addition to expanding
free trade, the administration would also seek negotiating
authority for new global trade deals in such areas as lowering
barriers to U.S. farm products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Gov't, Bundesbank Strike Compromise on Gold Revaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The German government today struck a
compromise deal with the central bank over its controversial plan
to revalue the bank's gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
The government and the central bank, known as the Bundesbank,
agreed Tuesday to revalue the bank's gold reserves closer to the
market price this year but delay the transfer of the surplus gained
from the move to the government until 1998 instead of 1997 as
initially planned.
</P>
<P>
The deal was struck by Finance Minister Theo Waigel and
Bundesbank President Hans Tietmeyer at a meeting in Bonn. Waigel
is due to formally announce the agreement in a speech to the
parliament on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to German media, the government is discussing
privatizations and more modest tax cuts as alternative measures to
plug an expected huge budget gap in order to enable Germany to
qualify for the planned single European currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Waigel reportedly wants to raise petrol taxes and delay cutting
an income tax surcharge to help raise funds.
</P>
<P>
But this is rejected by the Free Democratic Party (FDP), the
junior partner in Bonn's ruling coalition. Instead of tax rises,
the FDP wants to speech up privatization of states assets,
including German Lufthansa Airlines and the Deutsche Telecom
telephone company.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the German ruling coalition failed again to resolve
their internal dispute over the issue during a second round of
negotiations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
