<HEADLINE> Britain, Ireland Condition IRA Peace Talk with Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain and Ireland said today IRA's
political wing Sinn Fein would not be allowed to the multi-party
peace talks unless IRA called a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
An aide to Irish Foreign Minister Dick Spring told reporters in
Belfast that the two governments' patience was also running out.
</P>
<P>
"The patience of the two governments must not be presumed to be
inexhaustible," local reports quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party talks on Northern Ireland conflict resumed in
Belfast today after being adjourned three months ago for a British
general election that was held on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein was barred from attending the peace talks because the
outlawed IRA guerrillas has rejected to call a new cease-fire after
it quit a truce in February, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Northern Ireland secretary, Mo Mowlam, also showed
signs of impatience as she urged political leaders to agree on
disarming guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
"If Sinn Fein want to join the talks, there must be an
unequivocal restoration of the IRA ceasefire in words and
deeds...The ball is in their court," she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
However, talks chairman George Mitchell, a former U.S. senator,
expressed optimism over the new round after talks with British
Prime Minister Tony Blair on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that an opportunity exists to move forward in the
process and we hope very much that there will be substantive
progress in these talks in the near future," Mitchell told
reporters as the talks got under way. 
</P>
