<HEADLINE> Cohen Cautious on NATO's Membership of Balkan Nation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. has not decided whether
to support the membership of the Balkan nation of Slovenia in the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization, U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said today.
</P>
<P>
Prior to meeting with his Slovenian counterpart Tit Turnsek at
the Pentagon, Cohen said: "There has been no decision yet in terms
of who will be recommended for inclusion in the first round."
</P>
<P>
"That's something the president is taking under advisement," he
said, adding that no decision would be made before leaders of the
16-member alliance meet on July 8-9 in Madrid, Spain.
</P>
<P>
Poland, Hungary, the Czech Republic, Romania and Slovenia are
considered the front-runners to win membership invitations during
the first wave of NATO's expansion.
</P>
<P>
France, Italy and other southern European members of the alliance are
lobbying hard for Romania and Slovenia. But Washington
apparently favors only three in the first group.
</P>
<P>
However, Cohen added that Slovenia a former Yugoslav republic,
"has a very good record and certainly is under consideration" for
membership, but adding that "one cannot make any prediction at
this point."
</P>
<P>
Without giving details, Turnsek said he hoped his meeting with
Cohen would clarify some issues related to his country's bid for
NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
He noted that if Slovenia were not included in the first wave
of NATO's enlargement, Slovenia "will have to rethink the
strategy", but will continue to pursue a full NATO membership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
