<HEADLINE> U.S. Agrees to Renew Oil-for-Food Deal for Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Tuesday that it decided to support renewal of the U.N.
oil-for-food deal for Iraq after the agreement expires by June 7.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary (of State Madeleine Albright) has decided that
the United States will support the renewal of U.N. resolution 986
and that is the oil for food deal," State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan on Monday recommended the
renewal of the deal on the same terms: allowing Iraq to sell up to
$2 billion worth oil for six months and use use the money to buy
food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Most members of the U.N. Security Council had reportedly
expressed their approval of the renewal, but the United States has
not made the decision until now.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the United States had agreed to renew the deal
because the "agreement benefits the people of Iraq,... It does not
benefit in any way the government of Iraq." 
</P>
</TEXT>
