<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Outlows Two Guerrilla Groups in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain banned today two Northern
Ireland guerrilla groups which were responsible for violence over
the past year.
</P>
<P>
Mo Mowlam, Secretary of State for the province, had announced
earlier in the day that the pro-British Loyalist Volunteer Force
(LVF) and the pro-Irish Continuity Army Council (CAC) "will be
proscribed from midnight tonight (Tuesday)," according to a
government statement.
</P>
<P>
The ban was implemented in line with Northern Ireland's
Emergency Provisions Act which permits Mowlam to make an Order if
she believed an organization was concerned in terrorism or
promoting it.
</P>
<P>
The LVF split from Northern Ireland's mainstream Loyalist
movement, which is officially maintaining a ceasefire in its
campaign to maintain British rule of the province.
</P>
<P>
The CAC is a shadowy republican splinter group which was
thought responsible for an attempted car bomb in Belfast three
weeks ago and an attack on a country hotel in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Britain has already banned a number of terrorist groups in
Northern Ireland, including Irish Republican Army (IRA) which
launched military campaign against the rule of Britain on Northern
Ireland over the past 28 years, with some 3,200 people killed.
</P>
<P>
IRA was barred from attending a multi-party peace talks on the
Northern Ireland conflict which were resumed today because it
refuses to reach a ceasefire with government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
