<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Government's Budget Day Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chancellor, Gordon Brown will
deliver his first Budget on July 2, a Wednesday, instead of the
more traditional Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came in a written parliamentary answer as
evidence of strong manufacturing activity increased speculation
that the Bank of England may raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor confirmed that the Budget will be on July 2
because Prime Minister Tony Blair will be in China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The Budget is expected to introduce tighter fiscal policy to
take some of the heat out of the economy.
</P>
<P>
But City economists said survey evidence of the strength of
manufacturing output increased the likelihood that the Bank will
increase rates before the Budget.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing activity last month was at its highest level
since April 1995 according to a survey released yesterday by the
Chartered Institute for Purchasing and Supply.
</P>
<P>
Strong domestic demand is continuing to insulate manufacturers
from the soaring pound which is affecting exports badly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
