<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firms Encouraged to Set Up Businesses in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Embassy in Nigeria said
today the Chinese government encourages its companies to
establish businesses in the African country.
</P>
<P>
This is in line with China's policy toward promoting economic and
trade relations with foreign countries on the basis of equity and
mutual benefit, an embassy official in the commercial counselor's
office told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Further discussions are needed in this regard between the two
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The envoy made the remarks while asked to confirm a News Agency of
Nigeria (NAN) report which said Nigeria has reached broad agreements
with China for establishing processing companies in the Calabar Export
Processing Zone in the east of the country.
</P>
<P>
The NAN report quoted Nigerian Ambassador to China Zubairu Kazaure
as saying that this was one of the agreements with Chinese officials
during last month's visit of Chinese Premier Li Peng to the country.
</P>
<P>
The products of the proposed processing companies would be
re-exported to China to reduce the trade imbalance between both
countries, the Nigerian envoy said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, bilateral trade stood at 177 million U.S. dollars
last year, with Chinese exports to Nigeria amounting to 150 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Cautioning against an obsession to eliminate the imbalance, Kazaure
said China enjoyed trade surplus with many countries, which founds
Chinese products affordable.
</P>
<P>
He therefore advised Nigerian enterpreneurs to explore the
possibility of joint ventures with Chinese companies for the
processing of locally available products that could be exported to
China.
</P>
<P>
Kazaure identified cashew nuts, timber and timber products as well
as petroleum products as attractive in China, adding that Nigerians
should, however, be prepared for a highly competitive Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies are now engaged in railway rehabilitation, harbor
dredging and other projects in Nigeria. A textile joint venture has
been put into trial operation in the Calabar Export Processing Zone.
</P>
<P>
China provided to Nigeria last April four locomotives as the first
group of 50 of them listed in the railway project contract. But some
people in Nigeria are reportedly doubtful that the locomotives are
old.
</P>
<P>
Kazaure accused these unnamed people who were determined to realise
their private interests of being responsible for the rumours.
</P>
<P>
"I have seen the locomotives and there is nothing wrong with them,"
he told the Nigerian official news agency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
