<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Recommands Iraqi Oil Deal for Another Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today recommended a six-month renewal of the "oil-for-food"
deal for Iraq, UN spokesman Fred Eckhard announced.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Security Council, Annan said the deal, which
was authorized by the Security Council in its resolution 986 and
would expire on June 7, was unique among all humanitarian
assistance operations undertaken by the United Nations to mitigate
some of the negative effects of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in the light of the experience gained in the
implementation of the program in the past six months and the
continuing humanitarian crisis in Iraq, the deal should be
extended.
</P>
<P>
The current deal allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil over six months to buy food and medicine for its
people suffering from long time sanctions. UN imposed strict
economic sanctions on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in August
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
