<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Household Size Varies Greatly Among Countries, UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Average household size
ranged from 7.0 persons in Algeria to 2.1 persons in Sweden,
according to a UN yearbook published today.
</P>
<P>
The Demographic Yearbook 1995 features latest statistics and
indicators on household, family characteristics, marriage and
divorce from 111 countries and areas.
</P>
<P>
Among the 25 largest countries in the world, the biggest
average household size was in India, 5.5 persons per household,
and the smallest was in the United States, the Russian Federation
and France, which had 2.6 per household. China, which has a
population of 1.13 billion or one-fifth in the world, reported 4
persons per household.
</P>
<P>
Four other countries among the 25 largest ones reported an
average of 5 or more persons per household -- Philippines, 5.3;
Iran, 5.2; Mexico, 5.0; and Turkey 5.0. They are followed by Egypt
4.9; Viet Nam, 4.8; Indonesia, 4.5; and Brazil, 4.2.
</P>
<P>
Among the 25 African countries and areas covered by the book,
11 countries reported average household size of at least 5
persons, 12 had average household size of 4-5 persons; only 2
areas, namely Reunion and St. Helena, registered average household
size of less than 4 persons.
</P>
<P>
In North America, average household size of 5 or more was only
in Mexico; Colombia was the only country with average household
size of 5 persons or more in South Africa. In Asia 11 countries
reported an average size of 5 persons or more. In Europe, the
largest average household size was the former Yugoslav Republic of
Macedonia with 3.8 persons per household. In Oceania, average
household size ranged from 2.8 in New Zealand to 6.5 in the
Solomon Islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
