<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surging Economy Bypasses Black People in the US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy which is
expanding into seventh year is supposed to carry with it all types
of people, but low-skilled black people haven't quite caught the
wave.
</P>
<P>
Though the latest U.S. economic expansion has helped both
blacks and whites, it hasn't done much to narrow the gap between
them. Black workers are making just 76.5 percent of what white
workers make per week now, down from the 78 percent they made in
1990, according to The Wall Street Journal today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that black males in particular are losing
ground. The earning gap between black male college and high-school
graduates has widened four times as much since 1990, as has the
gap between their white counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment is running at 3.5 percent among college-educated
black men and 9.5 percent among black high-school grads. But
comparable figures for white college and high-school grads: 2.1
percent and 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The main reason by which blacks in the U.S. haven't benefit
much from the surging economy is the fact that small percentage of
them received high education. Only about 14 percent blacks
attended college. It left them unflexible in the changing economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
