<DOCNO> XIE19970604.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Court Grants IRA Bomb Suspect Bail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 3 (Xinhua) -- British High Court granted IRA bomb
suspect Roisin McAliskey a bail today after she gave birth to a
baby in a London hospital last week.
</P>
<P>
The court rule allowed 25-year-old McAliskey and her newborn
daughter Loinnir to move to a specialist mother and baby unit
instead of going to prison, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
McAliskey had been held in Britain's high security Holloway
prison since last year pending extradition to Germany for
questioning about an Irish Republican Army mortar attack at a
British army base in Osnabrueck.
</P>
<P>
Her mother Bernadette Mcaliskey said last week that security
officers even accompanied her daughter to ante-natal classes in
prison where the most intimate issues were being discussed.
</P>
<P>
"There is not one single supportable shred of evidence to
indicate that she has the most minimal knowledge of that offence,"
the mother said of accusations that her daughter was involved in
the Osnabrueck bombing last June.
</P>
<P>
McAliskey was granted bail as multi-party peace talks on
Northern Ireland resumed in Belfast. Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political wing, remains excluded from the talks until the IRA
declares a credible ceasefire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
